# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: 2024-united-states-presidential-election
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/107-days] As of September 30, 2025, the book has sold 350,000 copies in the United States, and is projected to sell at least 500,000 copies.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/107-days] CEO of Simon & Schuster Jonathan Karp said the book was one of the best-selling memoirs in the 2020s.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/107-days] As of January 2026, the book has been featured on the New York Times' Hardcover Nonfiction best-seller list for 15 weeks in a row.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/107-days] On July 31, 2025, Simon & Schuster announced that Harris would publish a memoir about her 2024 presidential campaign, with a release date of September 23.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/107-days] In a video posted on social media, Harris stated that the memoir was derived from a journal in which she wrote her reflections and recollections of "the shortest presidential campaign in modern history".
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/107-days] Harris collaborated with Geraldine Brooks to give the book a "novelistic feel", and Simon & Schuster CEO Jonathan Karp stated that the book reads more like a suspense novel than a political memoir.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/107-days] The memoir was coedited by Jonathan Karp and Dawn Davis, the senior vice president of Simon & Schuster.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/107-days] An audiobook version of the memoir narrated by Harris was announced to be published on Audible.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/107-days] On August 21, 2025, Harris announced on social media that she would be starting an international book tour in September 2025 to promote *107 Days*.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/107-days] She scheduled eighteen appearances in cities across the United States, Canada, and the United Kingdom; the first leg lasted through November 2025.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/107-days] In December 2025, Harris announced a second leg of the tour beginning in New Orleans on January 13, 2026, and finishing in Anaheim in April 2026.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/107-days] In the book, Harris calls leaving the decision to run for re-election solely up to Joe and Jill Biden "reckless".
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/107-days] Harris acknowledges Biden's age and health concerns, but says that Biden was still capable of functioning as president.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/107-days] Nonetheless, Harris states that she was "angry and disappointed" with Biden for his poor 2024 debate performance with then-former president Donald Trump, particularly because he did not understand how bad his performance was.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/107-days] In contrast to Biden, Harris did have a more well-received debate performance with Trump.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/107-days] Harris described her preparations for the debate in the book, which were led by Karen Dunn.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/107-days] Harris compared her loss, in which she lost the popular vote by 1.5% (48.3–49.8%) and the Electoral College 226–312, to the 2008 Super Bowl.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/107-days] She lost Wisconsin by 0.9%, Michigan by 1.4%, Pennsylvania by 1.7%, and Georgia by 2.2%.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/107-days] She quoted Tom Brady, who similarly described being surprised and devastated by his loss when the New England Patriots lost to the New York Giants 14–17.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/107-days] Harris does not say whether she will run for political office in the future in the book.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/107-days] She declined to run for Governor of California in the 2026 California gubernatorial election.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/107-days] Harris has expressed potential interest in running again for president in the 2028 United States presidential election.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/107-days] The book was positively reviewed by Jennifer Szalai of *The New York Times*, though Szalai acknowledged Harris's perspective was biased given she was defending her own record.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/107-days] *The Guardian* gave the book a largely negative review, largely due to its negative tone and inability to provide the reader with closure.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/107-days] It did not, however, criticize the book's writing quality.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/107-days] Democratic strategist Michael Hardaway criticized the book calling it "unhelpful" and saying it was "essentially a bunch of finger pointing and blaming others".
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/107-days] Smith questioned the point of the book, saying, "Who cares what [Kamala Harris] has to say? ...
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/107-days] More than 15 Democratic operatives across the country who were interviewed about their thoughts on the book criticized it, with one saying "If there's a political strategy here, it's a bad one.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/1788-1789-united-states-presidential-election] Presidential elections were held in the United States from December 15, 1788 to January 7, 1789, under the new Constitution ratified in 1788.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/1788-1789-united-states-presidential-election] George Washington was unanimously elected for the first of his two terms as president and John Adams became the first vice president.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/1788-1789-united-states-presidential-election] This was the only U.S. presidential election that spanned two calendar years without a contingent election and the first national presidential election in American history.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/1788-1789-united-states-presidential-election] Under the Articles of Confederation, which were ratified in 1781, the United States had no head of state.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/1788-1789-united-states-presidential-election] The executive function of government remained with the legislative similar to countries that use a parliamentary system.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/1788-1789-united-states-presidential-election] Federal power, strictly limited, was reserved to the Congress of the Confederation whose "President of the United States in Congress Assembled" was also chair of the Committee of the States which aimed to fulfill a function similar to that of the modern Cabinet.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/1788-1789-united-states-presidential-election] The Constitution created the offices of President and Vice President, fully separating these offices from Congress.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/1788-1789-united-states-presidential-election] The Constitution established an Electoral College, based on each state's congressional representation, in which each elector would cast two votes for two candidates, a procedure modified in 1804 by the ratification of the Twelfth Amendment.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/1788-1789-united-states-presidential-election] States had varying methods for choosing presidential electors.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/1788-1789-united-states-presidential-election] In five states, the state legislature chose electors.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/1788-1789-united-states-presidential-election] The other six chose electors through some form involving a popular vote, though in only two states did the choice depend directly on a statewide vote.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/1788-1789-united-states-presidential-election] The enormously popular Washington was distinguished as the former Commander of the Continental Army during the American Revolutionary War.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/1788-1789-united-states-presidential-election] After he agreed to come out of retirement, he was elected with ease unanimously; Washington did not select a running mate as that concept was not yet developed.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/1788-1789-united-states-presidential-election] No formal political parties existed, though an informally organized consistent difference of opinion had already manifested between Federalists and Anti-Federalists.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/1788-1789-united-states-presidential-election] Thus, the contest for the vice-presidency was open.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/1788-1789-united-states-presidential-election] Thomas Jefferson predicted that a popular Northern leader such as Governor John Hancock of Massachusetts or John Adams, a former minister to Great Britain who had represented Massachusetts in Congress, would be elected vice president.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/1788-1789-united-states-presidential-election] Anti-Federalists leaders such as Patrick Henry, who did not run, and George Clinton, who had opposed ratification of the Constitution, also represented potential choices.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/1788-1789-united-states-presidential-election] All 69 electors present cast one vote for Washington, making his election unanimous.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/1788-1789-united-states-presidential-election] Adams won 34 electoral votes and the vice presidency.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/1788-1789-united-states-presidential-election] The remaining 35 electoral votes were split among 10 candidates, including John Jay, who finished third with nine electoral votes.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/1788-1789-united-states-presidential-election] Three states were ineligible to participate in the election: New York's legislature did not choose electors on time, and North Carolina and Rhode Island had not yet ratified the constitution.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/1788-1789-united-states-presidential-election] Washington was inaugurated in New York City on April 30, 1789, 57 days after the First Congress convened.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/1788-1789-united-states-presidential-election] Both factions supported Washington for president.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/1788-1789-united-states-presidential-election] Limited, primitive political campaigning occurred in states and localities where swaying public opinion might have mattered.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/1788-1789-united-states-presidential-election] For example, in Maryland, a state with a statewide popular vote, unofficial parties campaigned locally, advertising.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/1788-1789-united-states-presidential-election] No nomination process existed at the time of planning, and thus, the framers of the Constitution presumed that Washington would be elected unopposed.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/1788-1789-united-states-presidential-election] Another uncertainty was the choice for the vice presidency, which contained no definite job description beyond being the president's designated successor and presiding over the Senate.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/1788-1789-united-states-presidential-election] The Constitution stipulated that the position would be awarded to the runner-up in the presidential election.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/1788-1789-united-states-presidential-election] Because Washington was from Virginia, then the largest state, many assumed that electors would choose a vice president from a northern state.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/1788-1789-united-states-presidential-election] Minister to France Thomas Jefferson wrote that he considered John Adams and John Hancock, both from Massachusetts, to be the top contenders.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/1788-1789-united-states-presidential-election] Jefferson suggested John Jay, John Rutledge, and Virginian James Madison as other possible candidates.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/1788-1789-united-states-presidential-election] Adams received 34 electoral votes, one short of a majority – because the Constitution did not require an outright majority in the Electoral College prior to ratification of the Twelfth Amendment to elect a runner-up as vice president, Adams was elected to that post.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/1788-1789-united-states-presidential-election] However, the states differed in their interpretations of this procedure and of the relevant portions of the new Constitution.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/1788-1789-united-states-presidential-election] New Hampshire and Massachusetts held a popular vote for their presidential electors alongside the elections for their representatives in the new Congress, on December 15 and December 18, respectively.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/1788-1789-united-states-presidential-election] In these two states, the legislatures ultimately chose the electors based on the voting results on the appointed day, January 7.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/1788-1789-united-states-presidential-election] In Delaware, Maryland, Pennsylvania, and Virginia, the electors were chosen directly by the popular vote on January 7.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/1788-1789-united-states-presidential-election] In Connecticut, Georgia, and South Carolina, the electors were appointed by the legislature alone on January 7, while in New Jersey the governor and council selected them on that day.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/1788-1789-united-states-presidential-election] The legislature in New York was unable to agree on a method for choosing the electors before January 7, and so the state could not appoint any electors.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/1788-1789-united-states-presidential-election] Voter turnout comprised a low single-digit percentage of the adult population.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/1788-1789-united-states-presidential-election] Though all states allowed some rudimentary form of popular vote, only six ratifying states allowed any form of popular vote specifically for presidential electors.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/1788-1789-united-states-presidential-election] In most states only white men, and in many only those who owned property, could vote.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/1788-1789-united-states-presidential-election] Free black men could vote in four Northern states, and women could vote in New Jersey until 1804.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/1788-1789-united-states-presidential-election] In some states, there was a nominal religious test for voting.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/1788-1789-united-states-presidential-election] For example, in Massachusetts and Connecticut, the Congregational Church was established, supported by taxes.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/1788-1789-united-states-presidential-election] Voting was hampered by poor communications and infrastructure and the labor demands imposed by farming.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/1788-1789-united-states-presidential-election] Two months passed after the election before the votes were counted and Washington was notified that he had been elected president.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/1788-1789-united-states-presidential-election] Washington spent eight days traveling from Virginia to New York for the inauguration.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/1788-1789-united-states-presidential-election] Congress took twenty-eight days to assemble.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/1788-1789-united-states-presidential-election] As the electors were selected, politics intruded, and the process was not free of rumors and intrigue.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/1788-1789-united-states-presidential-election] For example, Hamilton aimed to ensure that Adams did not inadvertently tie Washington in the electoral vote.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/1788-1789-united-states-presidential-election] Also, Federalists spread rumors that Anti-Federalists plotted to elect Richard Henry Lee or Patrick Henry president, with George Clinton as vice president.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/1788-1789-united-states-presidential-election] However, Clinton received only three electoral votes.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/1788-1789-united-states-presidential-election] Several respected sources, including the Biographical Directory of the United States Congress and the Political Graveyard, show this individual to be James Armstrong of Pennsylvania.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/1788-1789-united-states-presidential-election] However, primary sources, such as the Senate Journal, list only Armstrong's name, not his state.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/1788-1789-united-states-presidential-election] Skeptics observe that Armstrong received his single vote from a Georgia elector.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/1788-1789-united-states-presidential-election] Early presidential elections used a form of plurality block voting that preceded the widespread adoption of the general ticket.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/1788-1789-united-states-presidential-election] Under this system, voters elected each member of the Electoral College individually; electors nominated by the same political party often received differing numbers of votes as a consequence of voter rolloff, split-ticket voting, or electoral fusion.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/1788-1789-united-states-presidential-election] In most cases, this table calculates the popular vote of each state based on the votes for the leading Federalist and Anti-Federalist electors in each constituent county or township.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/1788-1789-united-states-presidential-election] In states where the electors were chosen from single-member districts, all votes for Federalist and Anti-Federalist electors are counted.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/1788-1789-united-states-presidential-election] Most townships in New Hampshire are missing data for this election; the figure shown is the result for the leading Federalist elector statewide.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/1788-1789-united-states-presidential-election] Because published compilations of the election results are missing labels for many electors, the estimate presented here is incomplete.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/1788-1789-united-states-presidential-election] As per the terms of the unamended constitution, each elector was permitted two votes for president, with a majority of "the whole number of electors appointed" necessary to elect a president.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/1788-1789-united-states-presidential-election] Of the 69 participating electors, each cast one vote for Washington, who was elected president.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/1788-1789-united-states-presidential-election] Of the remaining candidates, only Adams, Jay, and Hancock received votes from more than one state; with 34 votes, Adams finished second behind only Washington, and by virtue of which fact was elected vice president.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/1788-1789-united-states-presidential-election] Control of the bicameral New York State Legislature was divided following ratification of the federal constitution, and lawmakers could not reach an agreement to appoint electors for the forthcoming presidential contest.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/1788-1789-united-states-presidential-election] The fight to ratify the United States Constitution was still fresh in the memories of the legislators, and the Anti-Federalists were resentful for having been forced by events to accept the constitution without amendments.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/1788-1789-united-states-presidential-election] Bills to govern the selection of electors were proposed in each house and rejected by the other, leading to an impasse.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/1788-1789-united-states-presidential-election] The deadlock still stood on January 7, 1789, the last day for electors to be chosen by the states, and New York thus failed to appoint the eight electors allocated to it by the constitution.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/1788-1789-united-states-presidential-election] The Constitution, in Article II, Section 1, provided that the state legislatures should decide the manner in which their Electors were chosen.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/1792-united-states-presidential-election] Presidential elections were held in the United States from November 2 to December 5, 1792.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/1792-united-states-presidential-election] Incumbent President George Washington was elected to a second term by a unanimous vote in the electoral college, while John Adams was reelected as vice president.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/1792-united-states-presidential-election] Washington was essentially unopposed, but Adams faced a competitive re-election against Governor George Clinton of New York.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/1792-united-states-presidential-election] Electoral rules of the time required each presidential elector to cast two votes without distinguishing which was for president and which for vice president.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/1792-united-states-presidential-election] The recipient of the most votes would then become president, and the runner-up vice president.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/1792-united-states-presidential-election] The Democratic-Republican Party, which had organized in opposition to the policies of Secretary of the Treasury Alexander Hamilton, supported Clinton for the position of vice president.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/1792-united-states-presidential-election] Adams, meanwhile, was backed by the Federalist Party in his bid for another term.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/1792-united-states-presidential-election] Neither party had fully organized, and partisan divisions had not yet solidified.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/1792-united-states-presidential-election] Washington received 132 electoral votes, one from each elector.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/1792-united-states-presidential-election] Adams won 77 electoral votes, enough to win re-election.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/1792-united-states-presidential-election] Clinton finished in third place with 50 electoral votes, taking his home state of New York as well as three Southern states.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/1792-united-states-presidential-election] Two other candidates won the five remaining electoral votes.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/1792-united-states-presidential-election] This election was the first in which each of the original 13 states appointed electors, as did the newly added states of Kentucky and Vermont.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/1792-united-states-presidential-election] In 1792, presidential elections were still conducted according to the original method established under the U.S.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/1792-united-states-presidential-election] Under this system, each elector cast two votes: the candidate who received the greatest number of votes (so long as they won a majority) became president, while the runner-up became vice president.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/1792-united-states-presidential-election] The Twelfth Amendment would eventually replace this system, requiring electors to cast one vote for president and one vote for vice president, but this change did not take effect until 1804.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/1792-united-states-presidential-election] Because of this, it is difficult to use modern-day terminology to describe the relationship among the candidates in this election.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/1792-united-states-presidential-election] Washington is generally held by historians to have run unopposed.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/1792-united-states-presidential-election] Indeed, the incumbent president enjoyed bipartisan support and received one vote from every elector.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/1792-united-states-presidential-election] The choice for vice president was more divisive.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/1792-united-states-presidential-election] The Federalist Party threw its support behind the incumbent vice president, John Adams of Massachusetts, while the Democratic-Republican Party backed the candidacy of New York Governor George Clinton.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/1792-united-states-presidential-election] Because few doubted that Washington would receive the greatest number of votes, Adams and Clinton were effectively competing for the vice presidency; under the letter of the law, however, they were technically candidates for president competing against Washington.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/1792-united-states-presidential-election] Born out of the Anti-Federalist faction that had opposed the Constitution in 1788, the Democratic-Republican Party was the main opposition to the agenda of Treasury Secretary Alexander Hamilton.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/1792-united-states-presidential-election] They had no chance of unseating Washington, but hoped to win the vice presidency by defeating the incumbent, Adams.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/1792-united-states-presidential-election] Many Democratic-Republicans would have preferred to nominate Thomas Jefferson, their ideological leader and Washington's Secretary of State.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/1792-united-states-presidential-election] However, this would have cost them the state of Virginia, as electors were not permitted to vote for two candidates from their home state and Washington was also a Virginian.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/1792-united-states-presidential-election] Clinton, the Governor of New York and a former anti-Federalist leader, became the party's nominee after he won the backing of Jefferson and James Madison.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/1792-united-states-presidential-election] Clinton was from an electorally important swing state, and he convinced party leaders that he would be a stronger candidate than another New Yorker, Senator Aaron Burr.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/1792-united-states-presidential-election] A group of Democratic-Republican leaders met in Philadelphia in October 1792 and selected Clinton as the party's vice presidential candidate.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/1792-united-states-presidential-election] Madison was at first a Federalist until he opposed the establishment of Hamilton's First Bank of the United States in 1791.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/1792-united-states-presidential-election] He formed the Democratic-Republican Party along with Anti-Federalist Thomas Jefferson in 1792.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/1792-united-states-presidential-election] The elections of 1792 were the first ones in the United States to be contested on anything resembling a partisan basis.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/1792-united-states-presidential-election] In most states, the congressional elections were recognized in some sense as a "struggle between the Treasury department and the republican interest," to use the words of Jefferson strategist John Beckley.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/1792-united-states-presidential-election] In New York, the race for governor was fought along these lines.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/1792-united-states-presidential-election] The candidates were Chief Justice John Jay, a Hamiltonian, and incumbent George Clinton, the party's vice presidential nominee.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/1792-united-states-presidential-election] Although Washington had been considering retiring, both sides encouraged him to remain in office to bridge factional differences.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/1792-united-states-presidential-election] Washington was supported by practically all sides throughout his presidency and gained more popularity with the passage of the Bill of Rights.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/1792-united-states-presidential-election] However, the Democratic-Republicans and the Federalists contested the vice-presidency, with incumbent John Adams as the Federalist nominee and George Clinton as the Democratic-Republican nominee.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/1792-united-states-presidential-election] Federalists attacked Clinton for his past association with the anti-Federalists.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/1792-united-states-presidential-election] Congress counted the electoral results on February 13, 1793, with John Adams opening and reading the votes in his role as President of the Senate.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/1792-united-states-presidential-election] Washington was re-elected unanimously, receiving one vote from each of the 132 participating electors.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/1792-united-states-presidential-election] Adams received votes from 77 electors and Clinton 50; the four electors from Kentucky voted for Thomas Jefferson, and one South Carolina elector voted for Aaron Burr.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/1792-united-states-presidential-election] The distribution of the electoral vote between the four runners-up showed a high degree of party discipline, with only two electors voting contrary to the majority in their state.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/1792-united-states-presidential-election] Adams received the support of New England, South Carolina, and the Mid-Atlantic states (excepting New York), while Clinton carried New York and most of the South.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/1792-united-states-presidential-election] Nine of the 15 states eligible to choose representatives to the electoral college did so by a vote of the state legislature; the remaining six employed some form of popular vote.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/1792-united-states-presidential-election] Of these, complete returns from Maryland, Massachusetts, New Hampshire, and Pennsylvania survive; surviving returns from Virginia are incomplete, and popular vote records from Kentucky are not known to exist.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/1792-united-states-presidential-election] Of the states with complete returns, only Pennsylvania saw real partisan competition; a Federalist electoral slate pledged to Washington and Adams was selected, although one elector voted for Washington and Clinton.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/1792-united-states-presidential-election] At the time, party organizations were still in their infancy, and the partisan allegiance of the candidates was not always evident: it is therefore difficult to say whether the Pennsylvania vote for Clinton was an instance of a faithless elector, or an elector voting as pledged.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/1792-united-states-presidential-election] Elections in this period were vastly different from modern day presidential elections.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/1792-united-states-presidential-election] The actual presidential candidates were rarely mentioned on tickets and voters were voting for particular electors who were pledged to a particular candidate.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/1792-united-states-presidential-election] There was sometimes confusion as to who the particular elector was actually pledged to.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/1792-united-states-presidential-election] Results are reported as the highest result for an elector for any given faction.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/1792-united-states-presidential-election] For example, if three Federalist electors received 100, 50, and 25 votes, Federalist electors would be recorded as having 100 votes.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/1792-united-states-presidential-election] Confusion surrounding the way results are reported may lead to discrepancies between the sum of all state results and national results.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/1792-united-states-presidential-election] In Massachusetts, the best performing elector candidate for the Eastern District, Thomas Rice, was not selected by the Massachusetts General Court to be an elector.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/1792-united-states-presidential-election] Rice was a Federalist and his returns have been included into the state total below instead of the second best performing elector candidate.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/1792-united-states-presidential-election] The totals for Kentucky, Pennsylvania, and Virginia appear to be incomplete.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/1792-united-states-presidential-election] In several states candidates of unknown affiliation received votes.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/1792-united-states-presidential-election] The states chose 135 electors, out of whom 132 cast ballots.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/1792-united-states-presidential-election] (Two electors from Maryland and one from Vermont were absent and did not vote.) As per the terms of the unamended constitution, each elector was permitted two votes for president, with a majority of "the whole number of electors appointed" necessary to elect a president.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/1792-united-states-presidential-election] Each of the participating electors cast one vote for Washington, who was elected president.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/1792-united-states-presidential-election] The electors were split on their second choice: Adams received 77 votes to Clinton's 50, enough to secure a second-place finish behind Washington and the vice presidency.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/1796-united-states-presidential-election] Presidential elections were held in the United States from November 4 to December 7, 1796, when electors throughout the United States cast their ballots.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/1796-united-states-presidential-election] It was the first contested American presidential election, the first presidential election in which political parties played a dominant role, and the only presidential election in which a president and vice president were elected from opposing tickets.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/1796-united-states-presidential-election] Incumbent vice president John Adams of the Federalist Party defeated former secretary of state Thomas Jefferson of the Democratic-Republican Party.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/1796-united-states-presidential-election] With incumbent president George Washington having refused a third term in office, the 1796 election became the first U.S. presidential election in which political parties competed for the presidency.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/1796-united-states-presidential-election] The Federalists coalesced behind Adams and the Democratic-Republicans supported Jefferson, but each party ran multiple candidates.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/1796-united-states-presidential-election] Under the electoral rules in place prior to the Twelfth Amendment, the members of the Electoral College each cast two votes, with no distinction made between electoral votes for president and electoral votes for vice president.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/1796-united-states-presidential-election] The individual with the votes of a majority of electors became president, and the runner-up became vice president.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/1796-united-states-presidential-election] If there was a tie for first place or no person won a majority, the House of Representatives would hold a contingent election.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/1796-united-states-presidential-election] Also, if there were a tie for second place, the vice presidency, the Senate would hold a contingent election to break the tie.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/1796-united-states-presidential-election] The campaign was a bitter one, with Federalists attempting to identify the Democratic-Republicans with the violence of the French Revolution and the Democratic-Republicans accusing the Federalists of favoring monarchism and aristocracy.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/1796-united-states-presidential-election] Republicans sought to associate Adams with the policies developed by fellow Federalist Alexander Hamilton during the Washington administration, which they declaimed were too much in favor of Great Britain and a centralized national government.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/1796-united-states-presidential-election] In foreign policy, Republicans denounced the Federalists over the Jay Treaty, which had established a temporary peace with Great Britain.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/1796-united-states-presidential-election] Federalists attacked Jefferson's moral character, alleging he was an atheist and that he had been a coward during the American Revolutionary War.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/1796-united-states-presidential-election] Adams's supporters also accused Jefferson of being too pro-France; the accusation was underscored when the French ambassador embarrassed the Republicans by publicly backing Jefferson and attacking the Federalists right before the election.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/1796-united-states-presidential-election] Despite the hostility between their respective camps, neither Adams nor Jefferson actively campaigned for the presidency.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/1796-united-states-presidential-election] Adams was elected president with 71 electoral votes, one more than was needed for a majority.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/1796-united-states-presidential-election] He won by sweeping the electoral votes of New England and winning votes from several other swing states, especially the states of the Mid-Atlantic region.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/1796-united-states-presidential-election] Jefferson received 68 electoral votes and was elected vice president.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/1796-united-states-presidential-election] Former governor Thomas Pinckney of South Carolina, a Federalist, finished with 59 electoral votes, while Senator Aaron Burr, a Democratic-Republican from New York, won 30 electoral votes.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/1796-united-states-presidential-election] The remaining 48 electoral votes were dispersed among nine other candidates.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/1796-united-states-presidential-election] Several electors cast one vote for a Federalist candidate and one for a Democratic-Republican.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/1796-united-states-presidential-election] With Washington retiring after two terms, both parties sought the presidency for the first time.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/1796-united-states-presidential-election] Before the ratification of the 12th Amendment in 1804, each elector was to vote for two persons but was not able to indicate which vote was for president and which for vice president.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/1796-united-states-presidential-election] Instead, the recipient of the most electoral votes would become president and the runner-up vice president.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/1796-united-states-presidential-election] As a result, both parties ran multiple candidates for president, in hopes of keeping one of their opponents from being the runner-up.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/1796-united-states-presidential-election] These candidates were the equivalent of modern-day running mates, but under the law, they were all candidates for president.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/1796-united-states-presidential-election] Thus, both Adams and Jefferson were technically opposed by several members of their own parties.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/1796-united-states-presidential-election] The plan was for one of the electors to cast a vote for the main party nominee (Adams or Jefferson) and a candidate besides the primary running mate, thus ensuring that the main nominee would have one more vote than his running mate.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/1796-united-states-presidential-election] The Federalists' nominee was John Adams of Massachusetts, the incumbent vice president and a leading voice during the Revolutionary period.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/1796-united-states-presidential-election] Most Federalist leaders viewed Adams, who had twice been elected vice president, as Washington's natural heir.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/1796-united-states-presidential-election] Adams's main running mate was Thomas Pinckney, a former governor of South Carolina who had negotiated the Treaty of San Lorenzo with Spain.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/1796-united-states-presidential-election] Pinckney agreed to run after the first choice of many party leaders, former governor Patrick Henry of Virginia, declined.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/1796-united-states-presidential-election] Alexander Hamilton, who competed with Adams for leadership of the party, worked behind the scenes to elect Pinckney over Adams by convincing Jefferson electors from South Carolina to cast their second votes for Pinckney.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/1796-united-states-presidential-election] Hamilton did prefer Adams to Jefferson, and urged Federalist electors to cast their votes for Adams and Pinckney.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/1796-united-states-presidential-election] The Democratic-Republicans united behind former secretary of state Thomas Jefferson, who had co-founded the party with James Madison and others in opposition to Hamilton's policies.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/1796-united-states-presidential-election] Congressional Democratic-Republicans sought to also unite behind one vice-presidential nominee.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/1796-united-states-presidential-election] With Jefferson's popularity strongest in the South, many party leaders wanted a Northern candidate as Jefferson's running mate.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/1796-united-states-presidential-election] Popular choices included Senator Pierce Butler of South Carolina and three New Yorkers: Senator Aaron Burr, Chancellor Robert R.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/1796-united-states-presidential-election] Livingston, and former governor George Clinton.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/1796-united-states-presidential-election] A group of Democratic-Republican leaders met in June 1796 and agreed to support Jefferson for president and Burr for vice president.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/1796-united-states-presidential-election] Tennessee was admitted into the United States after the 1792 election, increasing the Electoral College to 138 electors.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/1796-united-states-presidential-election] Under the system in place before the 1804 ratification of the Twelfth Amendment, electors were to cast votes for two persons for president; the runner-up in the presidential race was elected vice president.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/1796-united-states-presidential-election] If no candidate won votes from a majority of the Electoral College, the House of Representatives would hold a contingent election to select the winner.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/1796-united-states-presidential-election] Each party intended to manipulate the results by having some of their electors cast one vote for the intended presidential candidate and one vote for someone besides the intended vice-presidential candidate, leaving their vice-presidential candidate a few votes shy of their presidential candidate.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/1796-united-states-presidential-election] But all electoral votes were cast on the same day, and communications between states were extremely slow at that time, making it very difficult to coordinate which electors were to manipulate their vote for vice president.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/1796-united-states-presidential-election] Additionally, there were rumors that Hamilton had coerced southern electors pledged to Jefferson to give their second vote to Pinckney in hope of electing him president instead of Adams.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/1796-united-states-presidential-election] Campaigning centered in the swing states of New York and Pennsylvania.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/1796-united-states-presidential-election] Adams and Jefferson won a combined 139 electoral votes from the 138 members of the Electoral College.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/1796-united-states-presidential-election] The Federalists swept every state north of the Mason–Dixon line except Pennsylvania, though one Pennsylvania elector voted for Adams.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/1796-united-states-presidential-election] The Democratic-Republicans won the votes of most Southern electors, but the electors of Maryland and Delaware gave a majority of their votes to Federalist candidates, while North Carolina and Virginia each gave Adams one electoral vote.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/1796-united-states-presidential-election] Nationwide, most electors voted for Adams and a second Federalist or for Jefferson and a second Democratic-Republican, but there were several exceptions to this.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/1796-united-states-presidential-election] One elector in Maryland voted for both Adams and Jefferson, and two electors cast votes for Washington, who had not campaigned and was not formally affiliated with either party.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/1796-united-states-presidential-election] Pinckney won the second votes from most of the electors who voted for Adams, but 21 electors from New England and Maryland cast their second votes for other candidates, including Chief Justice Oliver Ellsworth.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/1796-united-states-presidential-election] Those who voted for Jefferson were significantly less united in their second choice, though Burr won a plurality of the Jefferson electors.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/1796-united-states-presidential-election] All eight electors in Pinckney's home state of South Carolina, as well as at least one Pennsylvania elector, cast their ballots for Jefferson and Pinckney.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/1796-united-states-presidential-election] In North Carolina, Jefferson won 11 votes, but the remaining 13 were spread among six different candidates from both parties.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/1796-united-states-presidential-election] In Virginia, most electors voted for Jefferson and Governor Samuel Adams of Massachusetts.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/1796-united-states-presidential-election] Congress counted the electoral results on February 8, 1797, with John Adams opening and reading the votes in his role as President of the Senate.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/1796-united-states-presidential-election] Although some contemporary newspapers contested the legal validity of Vermont's electoral votes, no objections against them were raised in congress.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/1796-united-states-presidential-election] The result was that Adams received 71 electoral votes, one more than required to be elected president.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/1796-united-states-presidential-election] If any two of the three Adams electors in Pennsylvania, Virginia, and North Carolina had voted with the rest of their states, it would have flipped the election.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/1796-united-states-presidential-election] Jefferson received 68 votes, nine more than Pinckney, and was elected vice president.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/1796-united-states-presidential-election] Burr finished in a distant fourth place with 30 votes.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/1796-united-states-presidential-election] Nine other candidates received the remaining 48 electoral votes.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/1796-united-states-presidential-election] If Pinckney had won the second votes of all of the New England electors who voted for Adams, he would have been elected president over Adams and Jefferson.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/1796-united-states-presidential-election] Of the 138 participating electors, 70 voted for Adams and some other candidate and 67 voted for Jefferson and some other candidate; one elector from Maryland voted for both Adams and Jefferson, bringing their respective totals to 71 and 68.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/1796-united-states-presidential-election] With both parties' electors divided on their choice of a vice president, Jefferson finished second in the electoral vote ahead of Adams' intended running mate, Thomas Pinckney of South Carolina, making him vice president-elect.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/1796-united-states-presidential-election] Compiling reliable popular vote statistics for elections of the First Party System poses a challenge to historians.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/1796-united-states-presidential-election] Election procedures of the late 18th century differed greatly from those of later campaigns: rather than vote for a presidential candidate, voters chose from candidates running to represent their state in the electoral college.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/1796-united-states-presidential-election] Candidates for elector did not always advertise a party preference or even for whom they intended to vote; in some districts, candidates from the same party were in direct competition, while in others, inconsistent support for all candidates of a party led states to split their electoral votes.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/1796-united-states-presidential-election] These conditions make it difficult or impossible to determine voter intent in some cases.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/1796-united-states-presidential-election] Moreover, some states' returns have not survived to the present day, meaning that national popular vote totals in this article are necessarily incomplete.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/1796-united-states-presidential-election] The table below calculates each state's popular vote by comparing the vote for the most popular Adams elector to that for the most popular Jefferson elector.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/1796-united-states-presidential-election] In Massachusetts, the best performing elector candidates for the First Western and Second Middle Districts, Simon Larned and James Winthrop respectively, were not selected by the Massachusetts General Court to be electors.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/1796-united-states-presidential-election] Larned was a Democratic-Republican and Winthrop was a former Anti-Federalist.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/1796-united-states-presidential-election] The totals for Massachusetts and Virginia appear to be incomplete.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/1796-united-states-presidential-election] The following four years were the only time that the president and vice president were from different parties.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/1796-united-states-presidential-election] Calhoun were later elected president and vice-president as political opponents, but they were both Democratic-Republicans, and while Andrew Johnson, Abraham Lincoln's second vice-president, was a Democrat, Lincoln ran on a combined National Union Party ticket in 1864, not as a strict Republican.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/1796-united-states-presidential-election] On January 6, 1797, Representative William L.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/1796-united-states-presidential-election] Smith of South Carolina presented a resolution on the floor of the House of Representatives for an amendment to the Constitution by which the presidential electors would designate which candidate would be president and which vice president.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/1796-united-states-presidential-election] No action was taken on his proposal, setting the stage for the deadlocked election of 1800.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/1796-united-states-presidential-election] This is also the first of only two elections so far in the life of the Republic which elected a presidential term of only 1,460 days rather than 1,461 days (the second was in 1896).
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/1796-united-states-presidential-election] This is because of the Gregorian calendar rule that years ending in “00” but not divisible by 400, are not leap years.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/1796-united-states-presidential-election] The French foreign minister, Charles Delacroix, wrote that France "must raise up the [American] people and at the same time conceal the lever by which we do so...
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/1796-united-states-presidential-election] The foreign intrigue France perpetrated was unsuccessful, as Adams won the election with an electoral vote count of 71–68.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/1796-united-states-presidential-election] A significant factor in thwarting the French efforts was George Washington's Farewell Address, which condemned foreign meddling in America.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/1800-united-states-presidential-election] Presidential elections were held in the United States from October 31 to December 3, 1800.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/1800-united-states-presidential-election] This was the first presidential election in U.S. history to be a rematch, the first election where an incumbent president lost re-election, leading to the first time in modern history where a national government changed hands peaceably following a free election.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/1800-united-states-presidential-election] Adams had narrowly defeated Jefferson in the 1796 election.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/1800-united-states-presidential-election] Under the rules of the electoral system in place before the 1804 ratification of the Twelfth Amendment to the United States Constitution, each member of the Electoral College cast two votes, with no distinction made between electoral votes for president and electoral votes for vice president.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/1800-united-states-presidential-election] As Jefferson received the second-most votes in 1796, he was elected vice president.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/1800-united-states-presidential-election] In 1800, unlike in 1796, both parties formally nominated tickets.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/1800-united-states-presidential-election] The Democratic-Republicans nominated a ticket consisting of Jefferson and Aaron Burr, while the Federalists nominated a ticket consisting of Adams and Charles Cotesworth Pinckney.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/1800-united-states-presidential-election] Each party formed a plan by which one of their respective electors would vote for a third candidate or abstain so that its preferred presidential candidate (Adams for the Federalists and Jefferson for the Democratic-Republicans) would win one more vote than the party's other nominee.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/1800-united-states-presidential-election] The chief political issues revolved around the fallout from the French Revolution and the Quasi-War.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/1800-united-states-presidential-election] The Federalists favored a strong central government and close relations with Great Britain.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/1800-united-states-presidential-election] The Democratic-Republicans favored decentralization to the state governments, and the party attacked the taxes the Federalists imposed.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/1800-united-states-presidential-election] The Democratic-Republicans also denounced the Alien and Sedition Acts, which the Federalists had passed to make it harder for immigrants to become citizens and to restrict statements critical of the federal government.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/1800-united-states-presidential-election] The Democratic-Republicans were well organized at the state and local levels, while the Federalists were disorganized and suffered a bitter split between their two major leaders, Adams and Alexander Hamilton.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/1800-united-states-presidential-election] According to historian John Ferling, the jockeying for electoral votes, regional divisions, and the propaganda smear campaigns created by both parties made the election recognizably modern.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/1800-united-states-presidential-election] At the end of a long and bitter campaign, Jefferson and Burr each won 73 electoral votes, Adams won 65, and Pinckney won 64.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/1800-united-states-presidential-election] The Federalists swept New England, the Democratic-Republicans dominated the South, and the parties split the Mid-Atlantic states of New York, New Jersey, and Pennsylvania.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/1800-united-states-presidential-election] The Democratic-Republicans' assumption that one or more electors in Rhode Island, Vermont, New Jersey, Georgia, Kentucky, or Tennessee would vote for Jefferson and not Burr resulted in a tie, known as the Burr dilemma.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/1800-united-states-presidential-election] It necessitated a contingent election in the House of Representatives.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/1800-united-states-presidential-election] Under the terms laid out in the Constitution, the outgoing House of Representatives chose between Jefferson and Burr.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/1800-united-states-presidential-election] Burr was accused of campaigning for the presidency himself in the contingent election despite being a member of Jefferson's party.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/1800-united-states-presidential-election] Each state delegation cast one vote, and a victory in the contingent election required one candidate to win a majority of the state delegations.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/1800-united-states-presidential-election] Neither Burr nor Jefferson was able to win on the first 35 ballots of the contingent election, as most Federalist representatives backed Burr and all Democratic-Republican representatives backed Jefferson.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/1800-united-states-presidential-election] Hamilton favored Jefferson over Burr, and he convinced several Federalists to switch their support to Jefferson, giving Jefferson a victory on the 36th ballot.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/1800-united-states-presidential-election] Jefferson became the second consecutive incumbent vice president to be elected president.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/1800-united-states-presidential-election] This is one of two presidential elections (along with the 1824 election) that have been decided in the House.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/1800-united-states-presidential-election] Both parties used congressional nominating caucuses to formally nominate tickets for the first time.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/1800-united-states-presidential-election] The Federalists nominated a ticket consisting of incumbent President John Adams of Massachusetts and Charles Cotesworth Pinckney of South Carolina.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/1800-united-states-presidential-election] Pinckney had fought in the American Revolutionary War and later served as the minister to France.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/1800-united-states-presidential-election] The Democratic-Republicans nominated a ticket consisting of Vice President Thomas Jefferson of Virginia and former Senator Aaron Burr of New York.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/1800-united-states-presidential-election] Jefferson had been the runner-up in the previous election and had co-founded the party with James Madison and others, while Burr was popular in the electorally important state of New York.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/1800-united-states-presidential-election] While the 1800 election was a re-match of the 1796 election, it ushered in a new type of American politics, a two-party republic and acrimonious campaigning behind the scenes and through the press.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/1800-united-states-presidential-election] On top of this, the election pitted the "larger than life" Adams and Jefferson, who were formerly close allies turned political enemies.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/1800-united-states-presidential-election] The campaign was bitter and characterized by slander and personal attacks on both sides.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/1800-united-states-presidential-election] Federalists spread rumors that the Democratic-Republicans were radical atheists who would ruin the country (based on the Democratic-Republican support for the French Revolution).
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/1800-united-states-presidential-election] In 1798, George Washington had complained "that you could as soon scrub the blackamoor white, as to change the principles of a professed Democrat; and that he will leave nothing unattempted to overturn the Government of this Country".
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/1800-united-states-presidential-election] Meanwhile, the Democratic-Republicans accused Federalists of subverting republican principles with the Alien and Sedition Acts.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/1800-united-states-presidential-election] They also accused Federalists of favoring Britain in its war with France in order to promote aristocratic, anti-democratic values.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/1800-united-states-presidential-election] Ideology played a central role with a Jeffersonian "left" supporting the French Revolution, versus a Federalist "right" opposing it.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/1800-united-states-presidential-election] Adams was attacked by both the opposition Democratic-Republicans and a group of so-called "High Federalists" aligned with Alexander Hamilton.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/1800-united-states-presidential-election] "High Federalists" considered Adams too moderate and would have preferred the leadership of Alexander Hamilton instead.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/1800-united-states-presidential-election] Hamilton had apparently grown impatient with Adams and wanted a new president who was more receptive to his goals.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/1800-united-states-presidential-election] During Washington's presidency, Hamilton had been able to influence the federal response to the Whiskey Rebellion (which threatened the government's power to tax citizens).
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/1800-united-states-presidential-election] When Washington announced that he would not seek a third term, the Federalists and Adams regarded himself as next-in-line.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/1800-united-states-presidential-election] Hamilton appears to have hoped in 1796 that his influence within an Adams administration would be as great as or greater than in Washington's.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/1800-united-states-presidential-election] By 1800, Hamilton had come to realize that Adams was too independent and thought the Federalist vice presidential candidate, Charles Cotesworth Pinckney of South Carolina, more suited to serving Hamilton's interests.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/1800-united-states-presidential-election] In his third sabotage attempt toward Adams, Hamilton quietly schemed to elect Pinckney to the presidency.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/1800-united-states-presidential-election] Given Pinckney's lack of political experience, he would have been expected to be open to Hamilton's influence.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/1800-united-states-presidential-election] However, Hamilton's plan backfired and hurt the Federalist party, particularly after one of his letters, a scathing criticism of Adams that was fifty-four pages long, fell into the hands of a Democratic-Republican and soon after became public.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/1800-united-states-presidential-election] It embarrassed Adams and damaged Hamilton's efforts on behalf of Pinckney, not to mention speeding Hamilton's own political decline.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/1800-united-states-presidential-election] The contemporarily unorthodox public campaigning methods employed in 1800 were first employed by Jefferson's running mate and campaign manager, Aaron Burr, who is credited by some historians with inventing the modern electioneering process.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/1800-united-states-presidential-election] Yet, throughout this entire process, the candidates themselves were conspicuously missing from the campaigning, at least publicly, due to fears that they may otherwise be tagged as "demagogues".
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/1800-united-states-presidential-election] Even a visit John Adams made to Washington was made into a public point of contention.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/1800-united-states-presidential-election] Partisans on both sides sought any advantage they could find.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/1800-united-states-presidential-election] In several states, this included changing the process of selecting electors to ensure the desired result.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/1800-united-states-presidential-election] In Georgia, Democratic-Republican legislators replaced the popular vote with selection by the state legislature.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/1800-united-states-presidential-election] In Virginia, the Democratic-Republican-controlled legislature switched from electoral districts to a general ticket, a winner-take-all system.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/1800-united-states-presidential-election] Federalist legislators also switched methods, switching from districts and general tickets to legislature votes in Massachusetts and New Hampshire, respectively.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/1800-united-states-presidential-election] In Pennsylvania, the General Assembly was split, with the Democratic-Republican-dominated House wishing to retain the general ticket and the Federalist-controlled Senate wishing to return to the district system, hoping to win at least some electoral votes.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/1800-united-states-presidential-election] Eventually, this deadlock was broken by a last-minute compromise between the chambers that gave the Democratic-Republican eight electors and the Federalists seven.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/1800-united-states-presidential-election] In New York, the rejection to change the selection method backfired on the Federalists.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/1800-united-states-presidential-election] In March 1800, two months before the assembly elections, the Democratic-Republicans attempted to pass a bill that would switch from a legislature vote to electoral districts, hoping they would secure at least a third of the state's seats.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/1800-united-states-presidential-election] The Federalists defeated the measure, believing that they would win control of both chambers and award all of the state's electoral votes to the Federalist nominees.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/1800-united-states-presidential-election] However, in the April state elections, Aaron Burr's effective mobilization of the vote in New York City led to a reversal of the Federalist majority in the state legislature, providing crucial support for the Democratic-Republican ticket.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/1800-united-states-presidential-election] In response to the Federalist defeat, Hamilton attempted to get Governor John Jay to call a special session of the outgoing Federalist-dominated New York legislature.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/1800-united-states-presidential-election] Hamilton's plan was for the outgoing assembly to pass legislation that would establish the popular election of electors through electoral districts, a strategy almost certain to secure nine or ten of the twelve elector slots for the Federalists.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/1800-united-states-presidential-election] Jay refused to participate in such an underhanded scheme.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/1800-united-states-presidential-election] The Federalist legislature in Connecticut did not change the method of voting but instead passed a "stand up" election law, mandating that all votes be cast publicly and orally, an intimidating procedure that ordinarily favored those in power.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/1800-united-states-presidential-election] As election day neared, the election was too close to call.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/1800-united-states-presidential-election] The last state to vote, South Carolina, chose its electors on December 2, and would become key to determining the election.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/1800-united-states-presidential-election] The state elections in mid-October had produced an assembly that was about evenly divided between committed Federalists and Republicans, with 16 unaffiliated representatives who were all strongly pro-Jefferson.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/1800-united-states-presidential-election] Many of the elected Jeffersonians were also supporters of Pinckney, the revered native son of the state.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/1800-united-states-presidential-election] If South Carolina's electors gave their votes to Jefferson and Pinckney, then Pinckney would place an electoral vote behind Jefferson, becoming the vice president.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/1800-united-states-presidential-election] However, Pinckney stayed loyal to the instructions of his party's caucus and was adamant that any elector who voted for him must also vote for Adams.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/1800-united-states-presidential-election] With uncommitted legislators not willing to desert Jefferson and Pinckney unwilling to abandon Adams, the uncommitted legislators eventually reluctantly agreed to support Burr.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/1800-united-states-presidential-election] Under the United States Constitution as it then stood, each elector cast two votes, and the candidate with a majority of the votes was elected president, with the vice presidency going to the runner-up.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/1800-united-states-presidential-election] The Federalists therefore arranged for one of their Rhode Island electors to vote for John Jay instead of Charles Pinckney to prevent the election from resulting in a tie.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/1800-united-states-presidential-election] A letter to Jefferson from Peter Freneau assured him that a member of the Republican delegation from South Carolina would vote for George Clinton instead of Aaron Burr and a report from Georgia indicated that two of its electors would deny Burr their votes.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/1800-united-states-presidential-election] However, this information proved faulty.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/1800-united-states-presidential-election] Thus, all of the Democratic-Republican electors cast their votes for both Jefferson and Burr, 73 in all for each of them.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/1800-united-states-presidential-election] According to a provision of the United States Constitution, a tie in a case of this type had to be resolved by the House of Representatives, with each state casting one vote.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/1800-united-states-presidential-election] In the outgoing House, the Federalists had a majority of 60 seats to 46.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/1800-united-states-presidential-election] When the electoral ballots were opened and counted on February 11, 1801, the certificate of election from Georgia was different than the others.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/1800-united-states-presidential-election] Georgia had sent the original oral ballot.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/1800-united-states-presidential-election] In 2004, David Fontana and Bruce Ackerman asserted that Georgia's certificate did not take the constitutionally mandated form of a "List of all the Persons voted for, and of the Number of Votes for each".
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/1800-united-states-presidential-election] They claimed that Vice President Jefferson, who was presiding over the counting of electoral votes in his role as President of the Senate, immediately counted the votes from Georgia as votes for Jefferson and Burr, though they observed that "no objections were raised".
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/1800-united-states-presidential-election] Pinckney, and John Jay) in the House of Representatives.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/1800-united-states-presidential-election] With these votes, the total number of votes for Jefferson and Burr was 73, which gave them a majority of the total, but they were tied.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/1800-united-states-presidential-election] Holly Brewer, a legal historian, argued that the counting of the Georgia ballot did not support Ackerman and Fontana's theory.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/1800-united-states-presidential-election] Brewer's arguments helped to influence Vice President Pence's decision to reject the theory that he had such powers, via Judge J.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/1800-united-states-presidential-election] Jefferson and Burr carried every state that had supported the Democratic-Republicans in 1796, made gains in Maryland, and picked up Burr's home state of New York.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/1800-united-states-presidential-election] In the six states choosing electors by some form of popular vote, they won a landslide over Adams and Pinckney, polling 15,846 more votes than the Federalist ticket.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/1800-united-states-presidential-election] Adams made gains in Pennsylvania and North Carolina, but these votes were not enough to offset the Democratic-Republican gains elsewhere.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/1800-united-states-presidential-election] Of the 155 counties and independent cities making returns, Jefferson and Burr won in 115 (74.19%), whereas the Adams ticket carried 40 (25.81%).
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/1800-united-states-presidential-election] This was the last time that Vermont voted for the Federalists and the last time a Federalist won electoral votes from Pennsylvania.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/1800-united-states-presidential-election] This was the first of two elections contested between people who would at some point serve as vice president, the other being 1968.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/1800-united-states-presidential-election] Of the 16 states that took part in the 1800 election, six (Kentucky, Maryland, North Carolina, Rhode Island, Tennessee, and Virginia) used some kind of popular vote.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/1800-united-states-presidential-election] In Rhode Island and Virginia, voters elected their state's entire Electoral College delegation at large; Kentucky, Maryland, North Carolina, and Tennessee all used some variation of single-member districts.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/1800-united-states-presidential-election] In the rest, electors were chosen by the state legislature.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/1800-united-states-presidential-election] Not until the 1836 presidential election would all states have direct popular selection of electors (except South Carolina, which had its state legislature vote for electors until 1868).
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/1800-united-states-presidential-election] Popular vote records for several states are incomplete, and the returns from Kentucky and Tennessee appear to have been lost; states did not print or issue electoral ballots, and most were issued by newspapers that supported a particular party or candidate.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/1800-united-states-presidential-election] Newspapers are also the main source of voting records in the early 19th century, and frontier states such as Tennessee had few in operation, without any known surviving examples.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/1800-united-states-presidential-election] Kentucky, Maryland, North Carolina, and Tennessee chose each of their electors from specially-drawn single-member districts, the results from which are as follows.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/1800-united-states-presidential-election] In February 1801, the members of the House of Representatives balloted as states to determine whether Jefferson or Burr would become president.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/1800-united-states-presidential-election] There were sixteen states, each with one vote; an absolute majority of nine was required for victory.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/1800-united-states-presidential-election] It was the outgoing House of Representatives, controlled by the Federalist Party, that was charged with electing the new president.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/1800-united-states-presidential-election] Jefferson was the great enemy of the Federalists, and a faction of Federalist representatives tried to block him and elect Burr.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/1800-united-states-presidential-election] Most Federalists voted for Burr, giving Burr six of the eight states controlled by Federalists.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/1800-united-states-presidential-election] The seven delegations controlled by Democratic-Republicans all voted for Jefferson, and Georgia's sole Federalist representative also voted for him, giving him eight states.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/1800-united-states-presidential-election] The Vermont delegation was evenly split and cast a blank ballot.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/1800-united-states-presidential-election] The remaining state, Maryland, had five Federalist representatives to three Democratic-Republicans; one of its Federalist representatives voted for Jefferson, forcing that state delegation also to cast a blank ballot.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/1800-united-states-presidential-election] Publicly, Burr remained quiet between mid-December 1800 and mid-February 1801, when the electoral votes were counted.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/1800-united-states-presidential-election] Behind the scenes, he faced mounting pressure from within the party to step aside if he and Jefferson should tie in electoral votes.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/1800-united-states-presidential-election] Regardless, he refused to disavow the presidency, writing in December 1800 to Representative Samuel Smith (R-MD) that he would not "engage to resign" if chosen president, adding that the question was "unnecessary, unreasonable and impertinent".
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/1800-united-states-presidential-election] Rumors circulated that Representative James A.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/1800-united-states-presidential-election] Bayard (F-DE) had—purportedly in Burr's name—approached Smith and Edward Livingston (R-NY) with offers of political appointments if they voted for Burr.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/1800-united-states-presidential-election] Neither came to pass, however, chiefly due to Hamilton's energetic opposition to Burr.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/1800-united-states-presidential-election] Hamilton embarked on a frenzied letter-writing campaign to get Federalist Representatives to support Jefferson because he was "by far not so dangerous a man" as Burr; in short, he would much rather have someone with wrong principles than someone devoid of any.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/1800-united-states-presidential-election] From February 11 to 17, the House cast a total of 35 ballots; each time eight state delegations voted for Jefferson, one short of the necessary majority of nine.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/1800-united-states-presidential-election] On February 17, on the 36th ballot, Bayard changed his vote from Burr to no selection, joined by his allies in Maryland and Vermont.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/1800-united-states-presidential-election] This changed the Maryland and Vermont votes from no selection to Jefferson, giving him the votes of 10 states and the presidency.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/1800-united-states-presidential-election] The four representatives present from South Carolina, all Federalists, also changed their 3–1 selection of Burr to four abstentions.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/1800-united-states-presidential-election] Due to the experiences of this and the previous election, sentiment for a new way of selecting the president and vice president rose significantly, resulting in the Twelfth Amendment.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/1800-united-states-presidential-election] In the 2015 musical *Hamilton* by Lin Manuel Miranda, the contest between Jefferson and Burr is recounted in "The Election of 1800".
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/1800-united-states-presidential-election] The song focuses on Alexander Hamilton's role in deciding the outcome of the 1801 contingent election.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/1800-united-states-presidential-election] The musical simplifies the complicated multiple elections somewhat, portraying Adams's unpopularity as making the real choice between Jefferson and Burr.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/1800-united-states-presidential-election] Historians wrote that Adams did not lose that badly in the original election, with the musical inflating the size of Jefferson's victory.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/1800-united-states-presidential-election] It implies Hamilton's support for Jefferson over Burr was the catalyst for the Burr–Hamilton duel; in fact, while that helped sour relations between Burr and Hamilton, the duel was ultimately provoked by Hamilton's statements about Burr in the 1804 New York gubernatorial election.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/2024-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Presidential elections were held in the United States on November 5, 2024.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/2024-united-states-presidential-election-p01] The Republican ticket of former president Donald Trump and Ohio junior senator JD Vance defeated the Democratic ticket of incumbent vice president Kamala Harris and Minnesota governor Tim Walz.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/2024-united-states-presidential-election-p01] The incumbent president, Joe Biden of the Democratic Party, initially ran for re-election, easily sweeping aside a challenge from a Democratic representative in the Democratic primaries to become the party's presumptive nominee.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/2024-united-states-presidential-election-p01] However, what was broadly considered a poor debate performance in June 2024 intensified concerns about his age and health, and led to calls within his party for him to leave the race.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/2024-united-states-presidential-election-p01] After initially declining to do so, Biden ultimately withdrew from the race on July 21, 2024, becoming the first eligible incumbent president to run but subsequently withdraw since Lyndon B.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/2024-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Biden immediately endorsed Harris, who officially became the party's presidential nominee on August 5 and the first presidential nominee who did not participate in the primaries since Vice President Hubert Humphrey in 1968.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/2024-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Harris selected Walz as her running mate.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/2024-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Trump, who lost the 2020 presidential election to Biden, ran for reelection to a nonconsecutive second term.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/2024-united-states-presidential-election-p01] He was shot in the ear in an assassination attempt on July 13, 2024.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/2024-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Trump was nominated as the Republican Party's presidential candidate during the 2024 Republican National Convention alongside his running mate, Vance.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/2024-united-states-presidential-election-p01] The campaign also made false and misleading statements, including claims of electoral fraud in 2020.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/2024-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Historians and some former Trump administrators saw his political movement as authoritarian.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/2024-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Trump won the election over Harris, winning 312 Electoral College votes to Harris's 226.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/2024-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Trump won all of the top seven swing states, including Nevada for the Republicans' first time since 2004.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/2024-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Trump won the national popular vote with a plurality of 49.8%, making him the first Republican to win the popular vote since George W.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/2024-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Bush in 2004 (unlike his 2016 victory and 2020 defeat).
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/2024-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Trump's victory made him the second U.S. president to be elected to a nonconsecutive second term, after Grover Cleveland in 1892.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/2024-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Surveys of 2024 election voters, nationally and in key states, found that many viewed economic conditions negatively and were motivated by the issue when they voted.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/2024-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Other issues that motivated voters included immigration, the state of democracy, and abortion.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/2024-united-states-presidential-election-p01] In 2020, incumbent Republican President Donald Trump sought re-election but was defeated by Democratic challenger Joe Biden.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/2024-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Senator Kamala Harris of California was elected vice president in 2020 as Biden's running mate.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/2024-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Trump is the first president in American history to be impeached twice and run for president again after impeachment.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/2024-united-states-presidential-election-p01] As Trump was acquitted by the Senate in both cases, he was not barred from seeking reelection to the presidency in 2024.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/2024-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Supreme Court unanimously ruled in *Trump v.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/2024-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Anderson* that states cannot determine eligibility for a national election under Section 3.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/2024-united-states-presidential-election-p01] The Court held that only Congress has the authority to disqualify candidates, or to pass legislation that allows courts to do so.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/2024-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Trump made alleged false claims of voter fraud in the 2020 presidential election and denied the validity of the election results.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/2024-united-states-presidential-election-p01] In the lead-up to the 2024 election, the Republican Party made false claims of massive "noncitizen voting" by immigrants in an attempt to delegitimize the election in the event of a Trump defeat.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/2024-united-states-presidential-election-p01] The claims were made as part of larger efforts within the Republican Party to disrupt the 2024 election and promote election denial.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/2024-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Trump and several other Republicans stated that they would not accept the results of the 2024 election if they believed they were "unfair".
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/2024-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Trump's political operation said that it planned to deploy more than 100,000 attorneys and volunteers to polling places across battleground states, with an "election integrity hotline" for poll watchers and voters to report alleged voting irregularities.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/2024-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Before the election, U.S. officials and former officials stated that foreign interference in the 2024 election was likely.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/2024-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Three major factors cited were "America's deepening domestic political crises, the collapse of controversial attempts to control political speech on social media, and the rise of generative AI".
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/2024-united-states-presidential-election-p01] China, Russia, and Iran were identified as mounting influence operations and attempts to interfere with the 2024 election.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/2024-united-states-presidential-election-p01] U.S. intelligence officials described the efforts as part of broader efforts by authoritarian nations to use the internet to erode support for democracy.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/2024-united-states-presidential-election-p01] China was identified as interfering with the 2024 election through propaganda and disinformation campaigns linked to its Spamouflage operation.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/2024-united-states-presidential-election-p01] U.S. intelligence agencies described the effort as not targeting any particular candidate but focusing on issues important to the Chinese government, such as Taiwan, and "undermining confidence in elections, voting, and the U.S. in general".
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/2024-united-states-presidential-election-p01] As early as April 1, 2024, *The New York Times* reported that the Chinese government had created fake pro-Trump accounts on social media "promoting conspiracy theories, stoking domestic divisions and attacking President Biden ahead of the election in November".
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/2024-united-states-presidential-election-p01] According to disinformation experts and intelligence agencies, Russia spread disinformation ahead of the 2024 election to damage Biden and Democrats, boost candidates supporting isolationism, and undercut support for Ukraine aid and NATO.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/2024-united-states-presidential-election-p01] On September 4, 2024, the United States publicly accused Russia of interfering in the 2024 election and announced several steps to combat Russian influence including sanctions, indictments, and seizing of web domains used to spread propaganda and disinformation.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/2024-united-states-presidential-election-p01] U.S. intelligence agencies assessed that Russia preferred Trump to win the election, viewing him as more critical of American support for Ukraine.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/2024-united-states-presidential-election-p01] The Islamic Republic of Iran was identified as interfering with the 2024 presidential election through front companies connected to the Islamic Revolutionary Guard Corps and hacking attempts against the Trump, Biden, and Harris campaigns starting as early as May 2024.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/2024-united-states-presidential-election-p01] The Iranian regime launched propaganda and disinformation campaigns through fake news websites and accounts on social media to tip the election against former president Trump.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/2024-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Multiple Republican-led administrations removed voters from their states' voter rolls in the lead up to the election, which critics argued violates the National Voter Registration Act.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/2024-united-states-presidential-election-p01] In July 2024, 160,000 inactive or infrequent voters were removed from Ohio's voter rolls.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/2024-united-states-presidential-election-p01] The Ohio chapters of Common Cause and the League of Women Voters threatened lawsuits against the state over the purge.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/2024-united-states-presidential-election-p01] In August 2024, Governor Glenn Youngkin of Virginia signed an executive order removing 6,303 voters suspected of being non-citizens from Virginia's voter rolls.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/2024-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Department of Justice sued the Virginia Board of Elections and Virginia commissioner of elections over the voter purge, alleging that it violated the National Voter Registration Act.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/2024-united-states-presidential-election-p01] The suit also found a number of alleged non-citizens purged were actually citizens.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/2024-united-states-presidential-election-p01] District judge Patricia Tolliver Giles ruled that the removal was illegal, ordering the state to stop purging voter rolls and to restore the voter registration of more than 1,600 voters who had been removed.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/2024-united-states-presidential-election-p01] The 4th Circuit Court of Appeals then upheld the order.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/2024-united-states-presidential-election-p01] The administration filed an emergency appeal to the U.S.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/2024-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Supreme Court, which sided with Virginia in a 6–3 decision along ideological lines, allowing the state to continue purging voter rolls.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/2024-united-states-presidential-election-p01] In August 2024, Alabama Secretary of State Wes Allen announced a process for purging 3,251 registered Alabama voters and referred them to the state attorney general's office for criminal prosecution.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/2024-united-states-presidential-election-p01] In September 2024, the Department of Justice sued Alabama for violating the National Voter Registration Act.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/2024-united-states-presidential-election-p01] In October 2024, district judge Anna Manasco ruled in favor of the Department of Justice, ordering the state to restore the voter registrations.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/2024-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Alabama secretary of state's chief of staff Clay Helms testified that 2,000 of the purged voters were legally registered citizens.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/2024-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Trump was the subject of various criminal and civil legal proceedings before and during his 2024 re-election campaign.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/2024-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Specifically, Trump was found liable in a civil proceeding for financial fraud in 2023, was found liable for both sexual abuse and defamation in 2023, and was found liable for defamation in a related civil proceeding in 2024.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/2024-united-states-presidential-election-p01] In 2024, Trump was criminally convicted of 34 felonies related to falsifying business records.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/2024-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Trump and other Republicans made numerous false and misleading statements regarding Trump's various legal proceedings, including false claims that they were "rigged" or consisted of "election interference" orchestrated by Biden and the Democratic Party.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/2024-united-states-presidential-election-p01] On May 30, 2024, Trump was found guilty by a jury of all 34 felony counts in *The People of the State of New York v.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/2024-united-states-presidential-election-p01] The jury found that Trump falsified business records relating to hush money payments made to pornographic film star Stormy Daniels to ensure her silence about a sexual encounter between them.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/2024-united-states-presidential-election-p01] This conviction made Trump the first former U.S. president to be convicted of a crime.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/2024-united-states-presidential-election-p01] On January 10, 2025, Trump was given a no-penalty sentence known as an unconditional discharge.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/2024-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Trump faced other criminal charges as well.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/2024-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Trump*, Trump faced four criminal counts for his alleged role in attempting to overturn the 2020 United States presidential election and involvement in the January 6 United States Capitol attack; the case was dismissed following Trump's re-election in November 2024.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/2024-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Trump, et al.*, Trump was charged with eight criminal counts for his alleged attempts to overturn the results of the 2020 United States presidential election in Georgia.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/2024-united-states-presidential-election-p01] District Attorney Fani Willis was disqualified from prosecuting the case; Willis has appealed that decision.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/2024-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Trump, Waltine Nauta, and Carlos De Oliveira*, Trump faced 40 criminal counts relating to his hoarding of classified documents and alleged obstruction of efforts to retrieve them; the case was dismissed in July 2024.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/2024-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Trump*, an anonymous jury found Trump civilly liable for sexual abuse and defamation, and ordered him to pay Carroll $5 million in damages.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/2024-united-states-presidential-election-p01] In a related case brought by Carroll against Trump, a jury awarded Carroll $83.3 million.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/2024-united-states-presidential-election-p01] As of April 2025, appeals were ongoing in both cases.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/2024-united-states-presidential-election-p01] In September 2023, Trump was found civilly liable for financial fraud in *New York v.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/2024-united-states-presidential-election-p01] In February 2024, he was ordered to pay a $354.8 million fine, together with approximately $100 million in interest.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/2024-united-states-presidential-election-p01] As of January 29, 2025, an appeal was ongoing.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/2024-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Trump made efforts to delay his trials until after the 2024 election.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/2024-united-states-presidential-election-p01] On July 1, 2024, the Supreme Court delivered a 6–3 decision in *Trump v.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/2024-united-states-presidential-election-p01] United States*, ruling that Trump had absolute immunity for acts he committed as president within his core constitutional purview, at least presumptive immunity for official acts within the outer perimeter of his official responsibility, and no immunity for unofficial acts.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/2024-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Mass media, lawmakers, and Donald Trump raised concerns about Biden's age, including his cognitive state, during and after the 2020 United States presidential election.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/2024-united-states-presidential-election-p01] According to a February 2024 poll, Biden's age and health were major or moderate concerns for 86% of voters generally, up from 76% in 2020.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/2024-united-states-presidential-election-p01] According to another February 2024 poll, most of those who voted for Biden in 2020 believed he was too old to be an effective president; *The New York Times* noted that these concerns "cut across generations, gender, race and education".
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/2024-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Concerns about Biden's age and health increased after a poor performance by Biden during a debate against Trump in June 2024.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/2024-united-states-presidential-election-p01] That performance led a number of commentators and Democratic lawmakers to call for Biden to drop out of the 2024 presidential race.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/2024-united-states-presidential-election-p01] In July 2024, Biden ultimately withdrew from the race while stating that he would continue serving as president until the conclusion of his term.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/2024-united-states-presidential-election-p01] In the summer before the election, polling showed at least half of Americans thought that Trump, who was 78 years old, was too old to serve a second term, with 80% unsure he would be able to finish out a second term.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/2024-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Numerous public figures, media sources, and mental health professionals speculated that Trump may have some form of dementia, which runs in his family.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/2024-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Experts for the science publication *STAT* who analyzed changes in Trump's speeches between 2015 and 2024 noted shorter sentences, more tangents, more repetition, and more confusion of words and phrases.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/2024-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Doctors suggested these changes could relate to Trump's moods or could indicate the beginning of Alzheimer's.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/2024-united-states-presidential-election-p01] One expert noted an increase in expressions of all-or-nothing thinking by Trump; a sharp rise in all-or-nothing thinking is also linked to cognitive decline.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/2024-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Trump was also criticized for his lack of transparency around his medical records and health.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/2024-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Several scholars, lawmakers, intelligence agencies, and the members of the public expressed concerns about political violence surrounding the 2024 election.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/2024-united-states-presidential-election-p01] The fears came amidst increasing threats and acts of physical violence targeting public officials and election workers at all levels of government.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/2024-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Trump was identified as a key figure in increasing political violence in the United States both for and against him.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/2024-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Political violence was at its highest since the 1970s, and the most recent violence came from right-wing assailants.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/2024-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Trump increasingly embraced far-right extremism, conspiracy theories such as Q-Anon, and far-right militia movements to a greater extent than any modern American president.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/2024-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Trump also espoused dehumanizing, combative, and violent rhetoric, and promised retribution against his political enemies.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/2024-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Trump played down but refused to rule out violence following the 2024 election, stating "it depends".
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/2024-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Trump also suggested using the military against "the enemy from within" on Election Day that he described as "radical left lunatics", Democratic politicians, and those opposed to his candidacy.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/2024-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Trump filed and announced his candidacy a week following the 2022 midterm elections.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/2024-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Trump was considered an early frontrunner for the Republican presidential nomination.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/2024-united-states-presidential-election-p01] He had announced in March 2022 that his former vice president Mike Pence would not be his running mate.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/2024-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Trump faced opposition in the primaries.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/2024-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Florida Governor Ron DeSantis was initially viewed as the main challenger to Trump for the Republican nomination, having raised more campaign funds in the first half of 2022 and posting more favorable polling numbers than Trump by the end of 2022.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/2024-united-states-presidential-election-p01] On May 24, 2023, DeSantis announced his candidacy on Twitter in an online conversation with the social media company's CEO, Elon Musk.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/2024-united-states-presidential-election-p01] At the end of July 2023, *FiveThirtyEight*'s national polling average of the Republican primaries had Trump at 52 percent, and DeSantis at 15.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/2024-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Trump continued to win all four early voting contests while Haley's campaign struggled to gain momentum.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/2024-united-states-presidential-election-p01] On March 6, 2024, the day after winning only one primary out of fifteen on Super Tuesday, Haley suspended her campaign.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/2024-united-states-presidential-election-p01] On March 12, 2024, Trump officially became the presumptive Republican presidential nominee.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/2024-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Trump was injured in an assassination attempt on July 13, 2024, when a bullet grazed his ear.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/2024-united-states-presidential-election-p01] This was the first time a president or major party presidential candidate was injured in an assassination attempt since Ronald Reagan in 1981.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/2024-united-states-presidential-election-p01] On July 15, 2024, the first day of the Republican National Convention, Trump officially announced that Senator JD Vance of Ohio would be his running mate.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/2024-united-states-presidential-election-p01] On July 18, 2024, for the third consecutive time, Trump accepted the nomination from the Republican National Convention to become the Republican presidential nominee.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/2024-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Trump is the first major party candidate to have been nominated by their party for three or more consecutive elections since Franklin D.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/2024-united-states-presidential-election-p01] On April 25, 2023, President Joe Biden officially announced his re-election campaign, confirming that Vice President Kamala Harris would remain his running mate.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/2024-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Concerns about Biden's age were prominent, given that he was the oldest person to assume the office at age 78, which would make him 82 at the end of his first term and 86 at the end of a potential second term.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/2024-united-states-presidential-election-p01] An April 2023 poll indicated that 70 percent of Americans, including 51 percent of Democrats, believed Biden should not seek a second term, with nearly half citing his age as the reason.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/2024-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Biden's approval rating stood at 41 percent, with 55 percent disapproving.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/2024-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Speculation also arose that Biden might face a primary challenge from the Democratic Party's progressive faction; however, after Democrats outperformed expectations in the 2022 midterm elections, many believed Biden's chances of securing the party's nomination had increased.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/2024-united-states-presidential-election-p01] On July 28, 2022, Representative Dean Phillips of Minnesota became the first incumbent Democratic member of Congress to say Biden should not run for re-election and called for "generational change", pointing to Biden's age.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/2024-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Despite a handful of primary challengers, including Representative Dean Phillips, Robert F.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/2024-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Kennedy Jr., Marianne Williamson, and Jason Palmer, Biden easily became the party's presumptive nominee on March 12, 2024.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/2024-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Palmer, who won the American Samoa caucuses, became the first candidate to win a contested primary against an incumbent president since Ted Kennedy in 1980.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/2024-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Biden also faced significant opposition from uncommitted voters and the Uncommitted National Movement in their protest vote movement against Biden due to his support for Israel during the Gaza war, which collectively won 36 delegates.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/2024-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Following a "disastrous" June 2024 debate performance against Trump that "inflamed age concerns", Biden ultimately withdrew from the race on July 21, 2024, and immediately endorsed Kamala Harris to replace him in his place as the party's presidential nominee.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/2024-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Harris quickly announced her own presidential campaign later that day and by the next day, Harris had secured the non-binding support of enough uncommitted delegates that were previously pledged to Biden to make her the party's presumptive nominee.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/2024-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Biden's withdrawal made him the first eligible incumbent president since Lyndon B.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/2024-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Johnson in 1968 not to seek re-election, and the first to withdraw after securing enough delegates to win the nomination.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/2024-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Harris is the first presidential nominee who did not participate in the presidential primaries since Vice President Hubert Humphrey, also in 1968, and the first since the modern Democratic Party primary procedure was created in 1972 (prior to which most states did not hold primary elections).
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/2024-united-states-presidential-election-p01] On August 5, 2024, after five days of online balloting, Democratic National Convention delegates voted to make Harris the party's 2024 presidential nominee.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/2024-united-states-presidential-election-p01] She selected Minnesota Governor Tim Walz as her running mate the following day and accepted the party's nomination on August 22.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/2024-united-states-presidential-election-p01] A number of independent candidates announced presidential runs, most notably Robert F.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/2024-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Several third parties, including the Libertarian Party, the Green Party, the Party for Socialism and Liberation, the Constitution Party, and the American Solidarity Party also announced presidential nominees.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/2024-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Kennedy dropped out of the race in August 2024, although he remained on the ballot in many states.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/2024-united-states-presidential-election-p01] The No Labels organization abandoned its efforts to run a centrist candidate in April 2024.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/2024-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Chase Oliver was chosen by the Libertarian Party as its presidential nominee on May 26, 2024, at the 2024 Libertarian National Convention.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/2024-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Oliver was the party's nominee in the 2022 United States Senate election in Georgia.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/2024-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Oliver achieved ballot access in 47 states, and was eligible to receive write-in votes in the District of Columbia, Illinois, New York, and Tennessee.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/2024-united-states-presidential-election-p01] The party's nominee in 2012 and 2016, Stein is a physician and a former member of the Lexington Town Meeting.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/2024-united-states-presidential-election-p01] On August 16, Stein selected academic Butch Ware as her running mate.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/2024-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Stein achieved ballot access in 38 states, and was eligible to receive write-in votes in seven states.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/2024-united-states-presidential-election-p01] She was not eligible to receive write-in votes in the remaining states or the District of Columbia.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/2024-united-states-presidential-election-p01] These third-party candidates had ballot access in some states, but not enough to get 270 votes needed to win the presidency, without running a write-in campaign.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/2024-united-states-presidential-election-p01] The following notable individual(s) ran independently for president.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/2024-united-states-presidential-election-p02] Harris framed her campaign as "a choice between freedom and chaos" and based it around the ideals of "freedom" and "the future".
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/2024-united-states-presidential-election-p02] The Harris campaign sought to highlight her experience as an attorney general and a prosecutor to "prosecute the case" against Trump by pointing out his 34 felony convictions and the impacts of the overturning of *Roe v.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/2024-united-states-presidential-election-p02] Harris had taken liberal positions on a number of issues in her bid for the 2020 Democratic nomination; in 2024, she shifted several of those positions toward the political center and embraced many of Biden's domestic policy stances.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/2024-united-states-presidential-election-p02] Harris focused her economic proposals on the cost of groceries, housing and healthcare.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/2024-united-states-presidential-election-p02] A central campaign theme for Trump's second presidential bid was "retribution".
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/2024-united-states-presidential-election-p02] Trump framed the 2024 election as "the final battle", and openly promised to leverage the power of the presidency for political reprisals.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/2024-united-states-presidential-election-p02] Trump heavily ran on immigration as a central campaign focus.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/2024-united-states-presidential-election-p02] Trump's campaign focused on dark and apocalyptic rhetoric about the state of the country and predicting doom if he did not win.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/2024-united-states-presidential-election-p02] The Associated Press stated that "Trump's rallies take on the symbols, rhetoric and agenda of Christian nationalism." During his 2024 presidential campaign, Trump made numerous false and misleading statements.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/2024-united-states-presidential-election-p02] Trump has been described as using the "big lie" and firehose of falsehood propaganda techniques.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/2024-united-states-presidential-election-p02] Abortion access was a key topic during the campaign; it was on the ballot in up to 10 states in 2024, including the swing states of Arizona and Nevada.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/2024-united-states-presidential-election-p02] Abortion was a key issue for many voters in the 2022 elections.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/2024-united-states-presidential-election-p02] Of the states where abortion was on the ballot, measures seeking to expand or protect abortion access failed in Florida, South Dakota and Nebraska.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/2024-united-states-presidential-election-p02] Some pundits argued abortion rights referendums could help Harris in November.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/2024-united-states-presidential-election-p02] Democrats predominantly advocate for abortion access as a right, while Republicans generally favor significantly restricting the legality of abortion.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/2024-united-states-presidential-election-p02] Since becoming the presumptive nominee, Harris indicated her support for passing legislation which would restore the federal abortion right protections previously guaranteed by *Roe*.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/2024-united-states-presidential-election-p02] She argued Trump would let his anti-abortion allies implement Project 2025 proposals to restrict abortion and contraception throughout the United States.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/2024-united-states-presidential-election-p02] Trump claimed credit for overturning *Roe* but criticized Republicans pushing for total abortion bans.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/2024-united-states-presidential-election-p02] Trump said he would leave the issue of abortion for the states to decide but would allow red states to monitor women's pregnancies and prosecute them if they have an abortion.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/2024-united-states-presidential-election-p02] In his home state of Florida, Trump announced he would vote "No" on Amendment 4, an abortion rights referendum, preserving the six-week ban.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/2024-united-states-presidential-election-p02] The announcement came one day after he initially criticized the six-week ban for being "too short" and said he would vote to lengthen it.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/2024-united-states-presidential-election-p02] Trump repeated a false claim that Democrats support abortions after birth and "executing" babies.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/2024-united-states-presidential-election-p02] Border security and immigration were among the top issues concerning potential voters in the election.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/2024-united-states-presidential-election-p02] Polling showed that most Americans want to reduce immigration, and that a substantial minority of white Republicans were concerned about white demographic decline.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/2024-united-states-presidential-election-p02] In 2023 and early 2024, a surge of migrants entering through the border with Mexico occurred.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/2024-united-states-presidential-election-p02] Harris promised to fight for "strong border security" coupled with an earned pathway to citizenship.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/2024-united-states-presidential-election-p02] Harris highlighted her work in combating transnational gangs, drug cartels, and human traffickers while attorney general.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/2024-united-states-presidential-election-p02] As vice president, Harris announced in 2023 that she had garnered pledges of US$950 million from private companies to aid Central American communities to address the causes of mass migration, such as poverty.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/2024-united-states-presidential-election-p02] Harris stated she believes the immigration system is "broken" and needs to be fixed, and she said most Americans believe this.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/2024-united-states-presidential-election-p02] Harris also advocated for stricter asylum rules than Biden.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/2024-united-states-presidential-election-p02] Harris supported increasing the number of U.S.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/2024-united-states-presidential-election-p02] Border Patrol agents and accused Trump of being unserious on border security.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/2024-united-states-presidential-election-p02] As vice president, Harris also supported a bipartisan bill that would have funded additional border agents and closed the border if too crowded; the bill was rejected by Trump.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/2024-united-states-presidential-election-p02] Trump called on House and Senate Republicans to kill the bill, arguing it would hurt his and the Republican Party's reelection campaigns and deny them the ability to run on immigration as a campaign issue.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/2024-united-states-presidential-election-p02] Harris criticized Trump for his opposition to the bill on the campaign trail, and promised to sign the bill into law as president.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/2024-united-states-presidential-election-p02] Trump stated that if he were elected, he would increase deportations, send the U.S. military to the border, expand U.S.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/2024-united-states-presidential-election-p02] Immigration and Customs Enforcement detentions through workplace raids, deputize local law enforcement to handle border security, increase U.S.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/2024-united-states-presidential-election-p02] Customs and Border Protection funding, as well as finish building the wall on the southern border.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/2024-united-states-presidential-election-p02] Trump has said he will deport both legal and illegal immigrants.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/2024-united-states-presidential-election-p02] *The New York Times* reported that Trump was considering "an extreme expansion of his first-term crackdown on immigration", such as "preparing to round up undocumented people already in the United States on a vast scale and detain them in sprawling camps while they wait to be expelled".
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/2024-united-states-presidential-election-p02] Trump stated his intention to deport 11 million people through the construction of detention camps and deploy the military, relying on presidential wartime powers under the 18th-century Alien Enemies Act.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/2024-united-states-presidential-election-p02] Trump made false claims of a "migrant crime wave" that are not supported by data, and provided no evidence to back up his claims.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/2024-united-states-presidential-election-p02] In regards to his anti-immigrant nativism, Trump's tone grew harsher from his previous time as president, and used fearmongering, racial stereotypes, and more dehumanizing rhetoric when referring to illegal immigrants.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/2024-united-states-presidential-election-p02] Since fall 2023, Trump claimed that immigrants are "poisoning the blood of our country", which drew comparisons to racial hygiene rhetoric used by white supremacists and Adolf Hitler.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/2024-united-states-presidential-election-p02] In the 20 rallies that occurred after Trump's debate with Harris, *Politico* cited experts who found that Trump's rhetoric strongly echoed authoritarian and Nazi ideology; Trump made claims that immigrants are genetically predisposed to commit crimes and have "bad genes".
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/2024-united-states-presidential-election-p02] Climate change and energy policy played a role in the 2024 presidential campaign.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/2024-united-states-presidential-election-p02] In 2023, the United States saw a record in crude oil production with over 13.2 million barrels of crude per day, beating the 13 million barrels per day produced at the peak of Trump's presidency.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/2024-united-states-presidential-election-p02] The United States also dealt with supply shocks caused by the 2021–2024 global energy crisis due to the COVID-19 pandemic and Russian invasion of Ukraine.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/2024-united-states-presidential-election-p02] An advocate for environmental justice to address the impact of climate change on lower-income areas and people of color, Harris supported Biden's climate legislation.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/2024-united-states-presidential-election-p02] In 2022, Harris helped pass the Inflation Reduction Act, the largest investment in addressing climate change and clean energy in American history, putting the United States on track to meet emissions reduction targets by 50–52% below 2005 levels by 2030.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/2024-united-states-presidential-election-p02] Harris's campaign stated that she would not support a ban on fracking.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/2024-united-states-presidential-election-p02] Trump ridiculed the idea of man-made climate change, and repeatedly referred to his energy policy under the mantra "drill, baby, drill".
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/2024-united-states-presidential-election-p02] Trump said he would increase oil drilling on public lands and offer tax breaks to oil, gas, and coal producers, and stated his goal for the United States to have the lowest cost of electricity and energy of any country in the world.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/2024-united-states-presidential-election-p02] Trump also promised to roll back electric vehicle initiatives, proposed once again the United States withdrawal from the Paris Agreement, and rescind several environmental regulations.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/2024-united-states-presidential-election-p02] Trump stated his intention to roll back parts of the Inflation Reduction Act, Biden's signature domestic legislation.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/2024-united-states-presidential-election-p02] The implementation of Trump's plans would add around 4 billion tons of carbon dioxide to the atmosphere by 2030, also having effects on the international level.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/2024-united-states-presidential-election-p02] If the policies do not change further, it would add 15 billion tons by 2040 and 27 billion by 2050.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/2024-united-states-presidential-election-p02] Polling before the election indicated profound dissatisfaction with the state of American democracy.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/2024-united-states-presidential-election-p02] According to an October 25 ABC/Ipsos poll, 49% of Americans saw Trump as a fascist, described as "a political extremist who seeks to act as a dictator, disregards individual rights and threatens or uses force against their opponents".
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/2024-united-states-presidential-election-p02] Meanwhile, only 22% saw Harris as a fascist by this definition.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/2024-united-states-presidential-election-p02] Trump's 2024 presidential campaign was criticized by legal experts, historians, and political scientists for making increasingly dehumanizing, violent, and authoritarian statements.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/2024-united-states-presidential-election-p02] Trump's platform called for the vast expansion of presidential powers and the executive branch over every part of the federal government.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/2024-united-states-presidential-election-p02] Trump repeatedly stated his intention to have the Justice Department investigate and arrest his domestic political rivals, judges, prosecutors, and witnesses involved in his criminal trials.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/2024-united-states-presidential-election-p02] Calling the January 6, 2021, Capitol attack a "day of love", Trump promised to pardon those charged for their involvement and called them "hostages" and "great, great patriots".
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/2024-united-states-presidential-election-p02] Trump played down the possibility of violence if he were to lose the 2024 election, but did not rule it out altogether.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/2024-united-states-presidential-election-p02] Trump's 2024 campaign rhetoric has been described as fascist.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/2024-united-states-presidential-election-p02] Trump said his political opponents are a greater threat to the United States than countries such as Russia, China, and North Korea.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/2024-united-states-presidential-election-p02] Armed Forces be deployed on American soil to fight "the enemy from within", which—according to Trump—included "radical left lunatics" and Democratic politicians such as Adam Schiff.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/2024-united-states-presidential-election-p02] Trump repeatedly voiced support for outlawing political dissent and criticism he considers misleading or challenges his claims to power.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/2024-united-states-presidential-election-p02] Trump previously tried to have his political rivals prosecuted during his first term.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/2024-united-states-presidential-election-p02] Harris was tasked by Biden with protecting democracy through voting rights legislation through her work on the For the People Act.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/2024-united-states-presidential-election-p02] Harris supported efforts to defend election workers and counter Republican efforts to restrict voting following the 2020 presidential election.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/2024-united-states-presidential-election-p02] Harris also stated her intent to pass the Freedom to Vote Act and John Lewis Rights Voting Rights Advancement Act if elected.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/2024-united-states-presidential-election-p02] A December 2023 Gallup poll found a record low 28% of Americans reporting that they were satisfied with the way democracy is working in the country.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/2024-united-states-presidential-election-p02] In the weeks before the election, surveys showed that many favored a concession speech from the losing presidential candidate, had broad concerns about the state of democracy and were fearful of future acts of political violence.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/2024-united-states-presidential-election-p02] Surveys from the National Election Pool and VoteCast highlight the role the issue of democracy played in the election.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/2024-united-states-presidential-election-p02] According to results provided by the National Election Pool, 34% percent of voters said that the state of democracy mattered most to their vote.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/2024-united-states-presidential-election-p02] The poll found that 25% of those who cast a ballot said that democracy in the U.S. is secure, while 73% said it is threatened.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/2024-united-states-presidential-election-p02] VoteCast found that half of voters identified the future of democracy as the single most important factor for their vote.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/2024-united-states-presidential-election-p02] 9 in 10 Harris voters who said that democracy was the single most important factor expressed concern that electing Trump would bring the country closer to authoritarianism.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/2024-united-states-presidential-election-p02] About 80% of Trump voters who chose democracy as their top issue expressed concern about a Harris presidency becoming authoritarian.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/2024-united-states-presidential-election-p02] Voters consistently cited the economy as their top issue in the 2024 election.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/2024-united-states-presidential-election-p02] Following the COVID-19 pandemic, a global surge in inflation ensued that raised prices on many goods, although the U.S. inflation rate had declined significantly during 2023 and 2024.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/2024-united-states-presidential-election-p02] *The New York Times* reported that both candidates "embraced a vision of a powerful federal government, using its muscle to intervene in markets in pursuit of a stronger and more prosperous economy".
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/2024-united-states-presidential-election-p02] *The Wall Street Journal* reported that economists found Trump's proposed policies created a greater risk of stoking inflation and generating higher budget deficits, relative to the Harris plan.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/2024-united-states-presidential-election-p02] Twenty-three Nobel Prize-winning economists signed a letter characterizing the Harris economic plan as "vastly superior" to the Trump plan.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/2024-united-states-presidential-election-p02] Trump's designated government efficiency leader Elon Musk said in October that he expected Trump's plan would involve more than $2 trillion in federal spending cuts and would cause "some temporary hardship." Harris ran on a pro-union platform.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/2024-united-states-presidential-election-p02] She promoted the passage of the Infrastructure Investment and Jobs Act, funding for small business, and previously supported an act as senator to provide a $6,000 tax credit for middle and low-income families.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/2024-united-states-presidential-election-p02] Harris promised to address price gouging, bring down costs, ban hidden fees and late charges from financial institutions, limit "unfair" rent increases and cap prescription drug costs, which she said would "lower costs and save many middle-class families thousands of dollars a year".
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/2024-united-states-presidential-election-p02] In response to the housing crisis in the United States, Harris said she would increase home construction to reduce housing costs, arguing that it negatively impacts the economy and hurts working-class families.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/2024-united-states-presidential-election-p02] Harris proposed directing $40 billion to construction companies to build starter homes, and promised to send $25,000 in down-payment assistance to every first time home buyer.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/2024-united-states-presidential-election-p02] Trump proposed further individual and corporate tax cuts beyond the 2017 Tax Cuts and Jobs Act.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/2024-united-states-presidential-election-p02] Trump argued that keeping taxes low for the wealthy increases job creation, and that these policies coupled with a crackdown in illegal immigration and reduction in inflation would help the middle class.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/2024-united-states-presidential-election-p02] Trump said he would reduce regulation of business through the creation of an efficiency commission led by Musk, along with reducing environmental regulation.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/2024-united-states-presidential-election-p02] By October 2024, Musk was Trump's second-largest individual campaign donor.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/2024-united-states-presidential-election-p02] Trump said deporting millions of immigrants would bring housing prices down, although most economists argue it could raise prices by removing construction workers who use less real estate.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/2024-united-states-presidential-election-p02] Trump and Harris support not taxing tips for at least hospitality and service workers.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/2024-united-states-presidential-election-p02] Trump suggested that he would abolish the federal income tax and replace it with tariffs.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/2024-united-states-presidential-election-p02] In June 2024, Trump discussed the idea of eliminating the income tax in a private meeting with Republican politicians.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/2024-united-states-presidential-election-p02] In October 2024, Trump suggested that he would scrap the income tax if he wins, pointing out that tariffs were the main sources of revenue in the 19th century.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/2024-united-states-presidential-election-p02] Trump's stated trade policy involves the United States decoupling from the global economy and having the country become more self-contained and exerting its power through individual trade dealings.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/2024-united-states-presidential-election-p02] This would be attempted largely through a universal baseline tariff, set from 10% to 20% on all imports, with increased penalties if trade partners manipulate their currency or engage in unfair trade practices.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/2024-united-states-presidential-election-p02] Trump called for 100% tariffs on cars made outside the United States and a minimum 60% tariff on Chinese goods.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/2024-united-states-presidential-election-p02] Trump stated his plans to urge Congress to pass a Trump Reciprocal Trade Act to bestow presidential authority to impose a reciprocal tariff on any country that imposed one on the United States.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/2024-united-states-presidential-election-p02] *The Washington Post* reported in January 2024 that Trump was preparing for a massive trade war.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/2024-united-states-presidential-election-p02] Trump's trade policies were described as protectionist, neo-mercantilist, or autarkist, and increasing inflation became a more common critique of Trump's economic plans.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/2024-united-states-presidential-election-p02] In June 2024, 16 Nobel Prize in Economics laureates signed an open letter arguing that Trump's fiscal and trade policies coupled with efforts to limit the Federal Reserve's independence would reignite inflation in the United States.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/2024-united-states-presidential-election-p02] Moody's, as well as most economists surveyed by *The Wall Street Journal* in July 2024, predicted that inflation would be worse under Trump than Biden, a result due in part to tariffs, a crack down on illegal immigration, and larger deficits.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/2024-united-states-presidential-election-p02] Trump incorrectly insisted foreign exporters pay tariffs imposed by the U.S. government; American importers pay tariffs on goods upon arrival at U.S. ports, meaning tariffs are taxes that raise prices for imported products Americans buy.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/2024-united-states-presidential-election-p02] One non-partisan analysis estimated the proposed tariffs would cost $1,700 per year for the average household.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/2024-united-states-presidential-election-p02] The Committee for a Responsible Federal Budget found that Trump's plans would grow the national debt at roughly twice the rate of Harris' plan, while the Institute on Taxation and Economic Policy found Trump's plan would only benefit the top 5% of earners.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/2024-united-states-presidential-election-p02] Department of Education, claiming it has been infiltrated by "radical zealots and Marxists".
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/2024-united-states-presidential-election-p02] At the American Federation of Teachers national convention, Harris attacked recent efforts to ban books in school libraries.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/2024-united-states-presidential-election-p02] She also previously called for raising teachers' wages.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/2024-united-states-presidential-election-p02] Unlike previous elections, healthcare reform played a much more minor role in the 2024 presidential election.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/2024-united-states-presidential-election-p02] Harris stated that she no longer supported a single-payer healthcare system as she had in 2020.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/2024-united-states-presidential-election-p02] Instead, she said she intended to protect and expand items legislated during the Obama and Biden administrations.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/2024-united-states-presidential-election-p02] She said she would "maintain and grow" the Affordable Care Act, while Trump said that he would replace it with his own healthcare plan.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/2024-united-states-presidential-election-p02] Harris also supported limiting yearly out-of-pocket drug costs for seniors, and expanding the $35 cap on insulin for seniors on Medicare to younger individuals in the program as well.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/2024-united-states-presidential-election-p02] Generally, both candidates supported using the government to rein in prescription drug costs.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/2024-united-states-presidential-election-p02] Trump suggested he was open to cutting entitlement programs, such as Social Security and Medicare, part of an effort to "[cut] waste" as described by his campaign.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/2024-united-states-presidential-election-p02] During his first term, several budget proposals did suggest cuts to the programs.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/2024-united-states-presidential-election-p02] Additionally, Vance and Speaker of the House Mike Johnson suggested cuts to the ACA, including around pre-existing conditions, were part of Trump's plan.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/2024-united-states-presidential-election-p02] Kennedy Jr. dropped out of the race and endorsed Trump, Kennedy advocated for his "Make America Healthy Again" agenda, pledging to combat the upward trend in chronic disease patients, with Trump saying Kennedy would "go wild" regarding policy on food and medicines.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/2024-united-states-presidential-election-p02] The Russo-Ukrainian war, the Gaza war, and Chinese expansionism were some of the main foreign policy issues of the election.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/2024-united-states-presidential-election-p02] Harris signaled she would generally follow Biden's foreign policy on NATO and Ukraine, supporting both in the aftermath of the Russian invasion.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/2024-united-states-presidential-election-p02] A supporter of the two-state solution to the Israeli-Palestinian conflict, Harris advocated for "de-risking" from China, a policy that encourages reducing Western economic dependence on China.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/2024-united-states-presidential-election-p02] Harris was expected to continue deepening American alliances in Asia and the Pacific with the intention of curbing China's rising power both economically and militarily.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/2024-united-states-presidential-election-p02] Trump's 2024 campaign promoted an isolationist, "America First" foreign policy.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/2024-united-states-presidential-election-p02] Trump said that America's allies "treat us actually worse than our so-called enemies", and added: "We protect them and then they screw us on trade." He also vowed to impose tariffs on trade partners; economists said this could spark trade wars.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/2024-united-states-presidential-election-p02] He promised to "fundamentally reevaluate" NATO, shifting the country's defense spending from Europe towards Asia.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/2024-united-states-presidential-election-p02] Although NATO members are obliged to defend any other member who is attacked, Trump said he would encourage Russia to "do whatever the hell they want" to NATO allies that did not spend enough on defense.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/2024-united-states-presidential-election-p02] NATO Secretary-General Jens Stoltenberg responded: "Any suggestion that allies will not defend each other undermines all of our security." Trump vowed that even before he was inaugurated, he would negotiate an end to the Russo-Ukrainian war in one day.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/2024-united-states-presidential-election-p02] He promised to quickly cut the amount of military and financial aid to Ukraine, and make Europeans reimburse the United States the cost of rebuilding its old stockpiles; however, most of the money for Ukraine actually goes to American factories that make weapons and military equipment.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/2024-united-states-presidential-election-p02] Trump previously said he might recognize Russia's illegal annexation of Crimea, and suggested the 2022 invasion could have been prevented by Ukraine giving up parts of its own country to Russia.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/2024-united-states-presidential-election-p02] Trump promised a tougher stance against China, and at the same time questioned whether the United States should defend Taiwan.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/2024-united-states-presidential-election-p02] Trump suggested withdrawing troops from South Korea if it does not pay more to support American troops there.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/2024-united-states-presidential-election-p02] Polling indicated that the majority of voters support a ceasefire and American mediation in the Gaza war.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/2024-united-states-presidential-election-p02] According to a YouGov poll in March 2024, 52% of Americans supported stopping weapons shipments to Israel, coming largely from Americans who voted for Biden in 2020 (62% support) and people who did not vote in 2020 (60%).
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/2024-united-states-presidential-election-p02] Republicans opposed halting weapons shipments by 25 points.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/2024-united-states-presidential-election-p02] Republicans generally supported arms to Israel, while Democrats were divided on the issue.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/2024-united-states-presidential-election-p02] Harris largely continued Biden's approach to the Israeli–Palestinian conflict, although she was seen as more sympathetic to Palestinians than Biden or Trump.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/2024-united-states-presidential-election-p02] During the Gaza war, Harris supported Israel's offensive, saying "the threat Hamas poses to the people of Israel must be eliminated".
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/2024-united-states-presidential-election-p02] By March 2024, Harris was increasingly critical of Israel, calling for a ceasefire and two-state solution, and opposing the Rafah offensive, though still supporting the war overall.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/2024-united-states-presidential-election-p02] In the Democratic primaries, the Uncommitted National Movement led a protest campaign against Biden and later Harris over the war, calling for a ceasefire and arms embargo on Israel.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/2024-united-states-presidential-election-p02] It received over 700,000 votes and 36 delegates.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/2024-united-states-presidential-election-p02] Harris engaged with Uncommitted and Arab-American leaders, but refused to change her position.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/2024-united-states-presidential-election-p02] Harris argued for continued weapons shipments to Israel, saying it had a right to defend itself.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/2024-united-states-presidential-election-p02] Uncommitted ultimately encouraged its supporters to vote for Harris, though many were reluctant.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/2024-united-states-presidential-election-p02] Trump consistently supported Israel, though presented himself as the "candidate of peace".
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/2024-united-states-presidential-election-p02] Trump also supported giving weapons to Israel, likely with "no strings attached", saying that it must "finish the problem".
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/2024-united-states-presidential-election-p02] Trump was seen by some as more pro-Israel and less sympathetic to Palestine than Biden or Harris.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/2024-united-states-presidential-election-p02] Trump took a hardline stance against pro-Palestinian protests, telling donors he would "crush" them and deport non-citizen protestors to "set the movement back 25 or 30 years".
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/2024-united-states-presidential-election-p02] At times, Trump was critical of Israel's conduct, saying Israel should "get it over with ... get back to peace and stop killing people".
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/2024-united-states-presidential-election-p02] However, he pledged to end the war in Gaza through negotiation and bring peace to the Middle East.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/2024-united-states-presidential-election-p02] Trump called Biden's airstrikes on Yemen "crazy" and suggested negotiating with the Houthis.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/2024-united-states-presidential-election-p02] In the 2020s, conservative politicians in state legislatures introduced a growing number of bills that restrict the rights of LGBTQ people, especially transgender people.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/2024-united-states-presidential-election-p02] A strong supporter of LGBTQ rights, Harris denounced legislative attacks on transgender rights in states across the country.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/2024-united-states-presidential-election-p02] Exit polls showed that Harris had an 86%-12% advantage over Trump among voters who say that they are gay, lesbian, bisexual or transgender.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/2024-united-states-presidential-election-p02] Harris' lead among this group is the largest for a 21st-century Democratic presidential candidate with those reporting to be gay, lesbian, bisexual or transgender (2016–2024) and gay/lesbian/bisexual respondents (2000–2008).
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/2024-united-states-presidential-election-p02] Exit poll results for the 2012 election are not available.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/2024-united-states-presidential-election-p02] Trump promised to roll back policies regarding transgender individuals.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/2024-united-states-presidential-election-p02] Harris and Walz campaigned as supporters of LGBTQ+ rights.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/2024-united-states-presidential-election-p02] Trump stated he would rescind Biden's Title IX protections "on day one" for transgender students using bathrooms, locker rooms, and pronouns that align with their gender identities.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/2024-united-states-presidential-election-p02] Trump stated he would enact a federal law that would recognize only two genders and claimed that being transgender is a concept only recently manufactured by "the radical left".
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/2024-united-states-presidential-election-p02] Trump previously withdrew Title IX provisions that allowed transgender youth to have access to the bathrooms of their choice, and he attempted to roll-back several transgender-related policies in the Affordable Care Act.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/2024-united-states-presidential-election-p02] Trump repeated a false claim that children undergo transgender surgery while at school, without parental knowledge or consent.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/2024-united-states-presidential-election-p02] However, findings from an RCT study released by Ground Media/GLAAD said that the ad did not have an impact on who viewers intended to vote for.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/2024-united-states-presidential-election-p02] On July 13, 2024, Trump survived an assassination attempt while addressing a campaign rally near Butler, Pennsylvania.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/2024-united-states-presidential-election-p02] Trump was shot and wounded on his right ear by 20-year-old Thomas Crooks, who fired eight rounds with an AR-15–style rifle from the roof of a building approximately 400 feet (120 metres) from the stage; the shots killed one audience member and critically injured two others.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/2024-united-states-presidential-election-p02] Seconds later, Crooks was shot and killed by the U.S.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/2024-united-states-presidential-election-p02] On September 11, 2024, a bipartisan Senate report identified technical issues and other preventable mistakes by the Secret Service during the event.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/2024-united-states-presidential-election-p02] On September 15, 2024, Trump survived a second assassination attempt at Trump International Golf Club in West Palm Beach, Florida.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/2024-united-states-presidential-election-p02] The perpetrator, 58-year-old Ryan Wesley Routh, took position in nearby shrubbery holding an SKS-style rifle just outside the fence of the golf course.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/2024-united-states-presidential-election-p02] After hiding there for nearly 12 hours, Routh pointed his weapon through the fence line, approximately 400 yards (370 m) away from Trump.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/2024-united-states-presidential-election-p02] A Secret Service agent noticed this and fired four rounds towards Routh, who fled the scene and was later captured in Martin County.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/2024-united-states-presidential-election-p02] Routh was later indicted on five federal charges and three state charges, all of which Routh pleaded not guilty to.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/2024-united-states-presidential-election-p02] Two weeks later on September 23, Routh was found guilty on all federal counts, where he then grabbed a pen and attempted to stab himself in the neck, before being tackled by U.S. marshals.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/2024-united-states-presidential-election-p02] Routh was sentenced to life without parole on February 4, 2026.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/2024-united-states-presidential-election-p02] Since the 2020 election and continuing into the 2024 election, the election denial movement prompted thousands of death threats directed at election workers, officials, and their families, with some receiving letters laced with fentanyl.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/2024-united-states-presidential-election-p02] As of March 2024, the Department of Justice's Election Threats Task Force had charged 20 people with threat-related crimes.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/2024-united-states-presidential-election-p02] In September 2024, suspicious packages were sent to state election officials in several states, which resulted in evacuations.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/2024-united-states-presidential-election-p02] The inclusion of white powder in most of the packages mirrored the 2001 anthrax attacks; the substance in Oklahoma packages was identified as flour.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/2024-united-states-presidential-election-p02] Threats led some election workers to resign, and affected recruitment of temporary poll workers.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/2024-united-states-presidential-election-p02] In locations where funds were available, efforts to protect election workers involved active shooter training, provision of first aid kits and Narcan, bulletproof vests, bulletproof glass, metal detectors, armed guards, police snipers, and drones.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/2024-united-states-presidential-election-p02] On October 30, 2024, an 18-year-old man in Jacksonville, Florida, was arrested for aggravated assault and improper exhibition of a dangerous weapon after brandishing a machete at two women outside an early voting center.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/2024-united-states-presidential-election-p02] He, along with seven other teenagers, allegedly approached and antagonized members of the opposing political party as they were demonstrating.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/2024-united-states-presidential-election-p02] Neither the teenager's nor the women's political parties were disclosed, although later posts by the Duval Democratic Party described the teenager's party as a "group of young men carrying Trump flags".
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/2024-united-states-presidential-election-p02] On November 1, 2024, a voter wearing a "Let's Go Brandon" hat was reportedly struck by a poll worker after a verbal altercation over his hat at an Orangeburg County, South Carolina, polling location.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/2024-united-states-presidential-election-p02] Also on November 1, a man in Bath, New York, was arrested for assaulting someone in a supermarket for wearing a Trump hat.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/2024-united-states-presidential-election-p02] In late October 2024, multiple fires were reported at ballot drop boxes in Portland, Oregon, and Vancouver, Washington.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/2024-united-states-presidential-election-p02] The fires damaged hundreds of ballots, requiring election officials to identify and offer new ballots to those affected by the fires.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/2024-united-states-presidential-election-p02] Prior to the fires, the Federal Bureau of Investigation and the Department of Homeland Security had issued a bulletin raising concerns that "election-related grievances" could motivate domestic extremist activity and that ballot drop boxes could potentially be "attractive targets".
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/2024-united-states-presidential-election-p02] In Phoenix, Arizona, a fire was started in a mail collection box, destroying some ballots and other mail.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/2024-united-states-presidential-election-p02] A suspect was arrested and claimed that the fire was unrelated to the election.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/2024-united-states-presidential-election-p02] Following polling inaccuracies in connection with the 2020 presidential election, pollsters took steps to avoid similar errors in 2024.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/2024-united-states-presidential-election-p02] Pollsters used different approaches and methodologies for the 2024 election than what they had used previously.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/2024-united-states-presidential-election-p02] The polls also failed to reliably measure the preferences of Republican voters in GOP-leaning areas, Hispanic voters, and those who had voted in 2024 but not 2020.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/2024-united-states-presidential-election-p02] Despite efforts by pollsters to improve survey accuracy, national polls underestimated Trump's support once again in 2024.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/2024-united-states-presidential-election-p02] In 2016, national polls were fairly accurate; however, Trump overperformed the polls in Michigan, Pennsylvania, and Wisconsin, leading to his Electoral College victory.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/2024-united-states-presidential-election-p02] In 2020, polls had overestimated Biden's margin over Trump by approximately 4% in competitive states.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/2024-united-states-presidential-election-p02] In 2024, pollsters underestimated Trump's support by smaller margins than they did in 2016 and 2020, and their underestimation of that support was within the realm of a normal polling error.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/2024-united-states-presidential-election-p02] Going into the election, most polls showed the race to be neck and neck and within the margin of error.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/2024-united-states-presidential-election-p02] In every swing state, Trump outperformed his final polling numbers by approximately 3%, which is in line with a typical margin of error.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/2024-united-states-presidential-election-p02] Compared with the 2020 polls, the margin of error in 2024 in swing states was lower and high-quality national polls were more accurate.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/2024-united-states-presidential-election-p02] Polling averages vastly underestimated Trump's strength in both safe red and safe blue states.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/2024-united-states-presidential-election-p02] Florida and Texas were both projected to go for Trump by about 7%; he won each of them by about 13%.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/2024-united-states-presidential-election-p02] Pollster Ann Selzer released a poll in Iowa that had Harris winning the state by 3%, only for Trump to take the state by 13%.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/2024-united-states-presidential-election-p02] On the other hand, New Jersey was projected to be a safe state for Harris but most news stations waited until 90% of the vote was in before calling it for her, as she was only leading by 5%.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/2024-united-states-presidential-election-p02] Biden and Trump agreed to hold debates on CNN on June 27 and ABC News on September 10.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/2024-united-states-presidential-election-p02] Biden and Trump debated on June 27, 2024, in Atlanta, Georgia.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/2024-united-states-presidential-election-p02] After Biden suspended his re-election campaign on July 21, 2024, Harris became the Democratic nominee and debated Trump on September 10, 2024, in Philadelphia, Pennsylvania.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/2024-united-states-presidential-election-p03] Trump won the Electoral College with 312 electoral votes to Harris' 226.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/2024-united-states-presidential-election-p03] He prevailed in all of the seven swing states (Pennsylvania, Georgia, North Carolina, Michigan, Arizona, Wisconsin, and Nevada).
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/2024-united-states-presidential-election-p03] In addition, Trump won the national popular vote with a plurality of 49.8%; Harris received 48.3%.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/2024-united-states-presidential-election-p03] Cedric Richmond, co-chair the Harris campaign, announced on election night that Harris would not be speaking as originally planned.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/2024-united-states-presidential-election-p03] In the early hours of November 6, the day after the election, Trump was projected to win the election, and he declared victory at his Mar-a-Lago estate.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/2024-united-states-presidential-election-p03] Harris later conceded to Trump via a phone call, and publicly conceded the election to Trump that afternoon during a speech at Howard University.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/2024-united-states-presidential-election-p03] Candidates are listed individually below if they received more than 0.1% of the popular vote.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/2024-united-states-presidential-election-p03] Popular vote totals are from the Federal Election Commission report.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/2024-united-states-presidential-election-p03] Final reports as compiled from the certified vote totals of each state or district.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/2024-united-states-presidential-election-p03] The seven swing states in the 2024 election were the Rust Belt states of Wisconsin, Michigan, and Pennsylvania, as well as the Sun Belt states of Arizona, Georgia, Nevada, and North Carolina.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/2024-united-states-presidential-election-p03] Trump won the 2024 election with 58% of the electoral college—placing the win in approximately the 28th percentile of all presidential elections.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/2024-united-states-presidential-election-p03] in 2024 (shown in chart) places his victory in the 20th percentile of presidential election victory margins since 1828.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/2024-united-states-presidential-election-p03] Trump is the first president since Grover Cleveland in 1892 to win non-consecutive terms.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/2024-united-states-presidential-election-p03] 2024 also marked the first time since 1892 that the incumbent party had lost in each of three consecutive presidential elections.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/2024-united-states-presidential-election-p03] This was the first time since 1980 that the Democrats were voted out after a single four-year term.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/2024-united-states-presidential-election-p03] This was also the second consecutive election in which the incumbent party had lost after a single four-year term.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/2024-united-states-presidential-election-p03] Trump is the first Republican since George W.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/2024-united-states-presidential-election-p03] Bush in 2004 to win the popular vote (unlike his 2016 victory and his 2020 defeat).
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/2024-united-states-presidential-election-p03] Trump is also the second of only two presidents to win the Electoral College while losing the popular vote in a previous election but later winning both the Electoral College and the popular vote in a subsequent election.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/2024-united-states-presidential-election-p03] Trump is also the first non-incumbent Republican to have won the popular vote since George H.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/2024-united-states-presidential-election-p03] While winning the popular vote, Trump did not win a majority of the popular vote; he is the first winning presidential candidate since Bill Clinton in 1996 to win the popular vote with a plurality and also the first Republican since Richard Nixon in 1968 to do so.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/2024-united-states-presidential-election-p03] After Cleveland in 1884 and 1892, Woodrow Wilson in 1912 and 1916, and Clinton in 1992 and 1996, Trump became the fourth president since 1880 to win two presidential elections and receive less than 50% of the popular vote in both presidential election victories.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/2024-united-states-presidential-election-p03] Trump is the first presidential candidate since Barack Obama in 2012 to win a second term in the White House and also the first Republican since George W.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/2024-united-states-presidential-election-p03] Trump is also the first presidential candidate since Nixon in 1968 to successfully make a political comeback by winning an election after losing a previous one.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/2024-united-states-presidential-election-p03] Trump is the first Republican presidential candidate to win Nevada since George W.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/2024-united-states-presidential-election-p03] The 2024 presidential election was the first presidential election since 1976 in which all 50 states and Washington, D.C. shifted towards the same party.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/2024-united-states-presidential-election-p03] Approximately 90% of counties swung towards Trump between the 2020 and 2024 elections, encompassing both rural and urban areas.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/2024-united-states-presidential-election-p03] The 2024 election was the first presidential election since 1932 in which the losing candidate failed to flip a single county.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/2024-united-states-presidential-election-p03] Even among states that voted heavily for Biden in the 2020 election, Trump's gains were significant.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/2024-united-states-presidential-election-p03] The states of New York and New Jersey swung over ten points toward Trump, and Trump also made gains in Harris' home state of California.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/2024-united-states-presidential-election-p03] However, relative to 2016, only 28 states shifted to the right by 2024, with an average shift relative to 2016 of 1 point.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/2024-united-states-presidential-election-p03] While Trump made gains among young voters compared to Republicans in recent presidential elections, especially among young men, exit polls found Harris won young voters by 54 to 51 percent of voters under 30.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/2024-united-states-presidential-election-p03] However, Millennials and Generation Z constituted a minority of the voting public.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/2024-united-states-presidential-election-p03] Voters 44 years of age or younger (born in 1980 or later) were estimated by the exit poll to comprise 37% of the electorate.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/2024-united-states-presidential-election-p03] According to exit polls, Harris's strongest income demographic consisted of voters making over $200,000 a year; she won those voters by a margin of 52–46%.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/2024-united-states-presidential-election-p03] Post-election research by the Brookings Institution found that while Trump made inroads with minority voters, the Republican Party had "hardly" created a multiracial coalition.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/2024-united-states-presidential-election-p03] Brookings argued that saying so was premature and that such support "could very well be a blip" based on economic concerns.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/2024-united-states-presidential-election-p03] At age 78, Trump is the oldest non-incumbent ever to win a presidential election, and also the oldest president ever elected, surpassing Biden's both records in 2020, who was elected at age 77; Trump is also the first former president to win a state since Theodore Roosevelt in 1912.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/2024-united-states-presidential-election-p03] This was the first election since 1944 in which a presidential candidate won two elections with different vice presidential candidates; Trump replaced his 2016 and 2020 running mate, Mike Pence, with Vance.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/2024-united-states-presidential-election-p03] Crisis services for the LGBTQ+ community saw a sharp increase in usage during the election week.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/2024-united-states-presidential-election-p03] The Trevor Project's crisis lines saw a 125% increase since around midnight on election night according to a statement by CEO Jaymes Black on November 6, and followed an about 200% increase in election related conversations that had been seen between November 3–4.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/2024-united-states-presidential-election-p03] By November 8, it was reported that the organization saw an overall increase by 700%.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/2024-united-states-presidential-election-p03] The Crisis Text Line also reported that 56% of their users reported as LGBTQ+ on election day.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/2024-united-states-presidential-election-p03] A company that assists wealthy Americans in securing foreign citizenship saw a 200× jump in inquiries following the election.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/2024-united-states-presidential-election-p03] Democrats had differing views on why Harris lost the election.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/2024-united-states-presidential-election-p03] Vermont Senator Bernie Sanders blamed Democrats for having abandoned the working class.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/2024-united-states-presidential-election-p03] Democratic National Committee chair Jaime Harrison dismissed Sanders' criticism.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/2024-united-states-presidential-election-p03] Former House Speaker Nancy Pelosi also disagreed with Sanders, blaming the party's loss on Biden's late exit and the lack of an open Democratic primary.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/2024-united-states-presidential-election-p03] Senator Chris Murphy (D-CT) believed that the Democrats could not connect to a large number of voters and should embrace populism going forward.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/2024-united-states-presidential-election-p03] Representative Ritchie Torres (D-NY) attributed Trump's victory to public discontent over inflation and immigration; he asserted that Harris ran an effective campaign, but could not overcome a difficult electoral environment.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/2024-united-states-presidential-election-p03] Wall Street's main indexes reported record highs on the day after the election, with the Dow Jones Industrial Average up 3.57%, the S&P 500 up 2.53%, and Nasdaq up 2.95%.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/2024-united-states-presidential-election-p03] Following Trump's victory, some Harris supporters on X shared election denial conspiracy theories, claiming that millions of ballots were "left uncounted" and there being something "not right" with the election.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/2024-united-states-presidential-election-p03] Such posts falsely claiming Trump "stole" the election peaked at noon the day after at 94,000 posts per hour, with many receiving amplification and gaining over a million views each.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/2024-united-states-presidential-election-p03] According to Gordon Crovitz, the CEO of the media rating system NewsGuard, the phrase "Trump cheated" received 92,100 mentions on the platform from midnight until the Wednesday morning after.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/2024-united-states-presidential-election-p03] Besides the claims from Harris's supporters, some Trump supporters baselessly claimed the disparity between other years, the 2020 election, and a then-incomplete 2024 voting total indicated voter fraud in the 2020 election.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/2024-united-states-presidential-election-p03] One major "basis" these false claims were founded upon was a claim that Biden won 20 million more votes in his prior election bid than Harris had in hers, at the time.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/2024-united-states-presidential-election-p03] American journalist and conspiracy theorist Wayne Madsen commented on Threads: "I'm beginning to believe our election was massively hacked just like happened a few weeks ago in the Republic of Georgia." At the time these claims were disseminated, votes were still being counted in many states.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/2024-united-states-presidential-election-p03] An estimate around the time using the Associated Press vote percentage total found that 16.2 million votes across 20 states and D.C. had yet to be counted.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/2024-united-states-presidential-election-p03] Statistical analysis of voting asserted that despite continued counting, the projections were already set and new ballots would not sway the outcomes of any of the states and D.C.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/2024-united-states-presidential-election-p03] The Cybersecurity and Infrastructure Security Agency director Jen Easterly refuted the false claims, and wrote in a statement that there was "no evidence of any malicious activity that had a material impact on the security or integrity of our election infrastructure".
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/2024-united-states-presidential-election-p03] Another false claim alleges Musk used the satellite Internet constellation Starlink to change the results of the election.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/2024-united-states-presidential-election-p03] Chief technology officer Chip Trowbridge of voting system manufacturer Clear Ballot dismissed the claim and added that no machines used to scan voting ballots have any network connection whatsoever.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/2024-united-states-presidential-election-p03] Numerous Black Americans across multiple states reported receiving threatening, racist text messages the day after the election.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/2024-united-states-presidential-election-p03] Some of the texts referenced the incoming Trump administration, but the senders remained unknown as of November 10, 2024.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/2024-united-states-presidential-election-p03] Days later, several Latino and LGBTQIA students also reported receiving similar harassment through text messages and emails.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/2024-united-states-presidential-election-p03] Harris's loss to Trump received substantial media analysis in the aftermath of the election.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/2024-united-states-presidential-election-p03] Proposed explanations for the outcome of the race included inflation, the immigration crisis, a global incumbency backlash, Biden's late exit from the race, and the lack of an open Democratic primary process.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/2024-united-states-presidential-election-p03] Democrats and others argued about what went wrong and how the party should move forward.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/2024-united-states-presidential-election-p03] According to Gallup, most factors with respect to the electoral environment favored Republicans and Trump.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/2024-united-states-presidential-election-p03] These included low confidence in the economy, Republicans outnumbering Democrats in party affiliation (48–45%), low national satisfaction, Republicans being favored to address the economy and immigration, and Biden's low job approval rating.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/2024-united-states-presidential-election-p03] Harris was viewed more favorably on character and had an advantage on some issues.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/2024-united-states-presidential-election-p03] No incumbent party has won when a president had below a 45% approval rating, either losing reelection (Jimmy Carter in 1980, George H.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/2024-united-states-presidential-election-p03] Bush in 1992, and Trump himself in 2020) or the incumbent party lost the White House (Hubert Humphrey in 1968).
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/2024-united-states-presidential-election-p03] According to exit polls, voters disapproved of Biden's performance 59–39%, and disapproved of how things were going in the United States 73–25%.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/2024-united-states-presidential-election-p03] Also, voters judged the economy negatively 68–32%, and said that inflation had caused them hardship 75–24%.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/2024-united-states-presidential-election-p03] A YouGov poll conducted from November 6–7, 2024 found that if Biden had been the Democratic nominee, Trump would have won the popular vote 49–42%.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/2024-united-states-presidential-election-p03] Nonpartisan election forecasters, including *The Cook Political Report* and *Sabato's Crystal Ball*, stated before the election that Biden would have been almost certain to lose.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/2024-united-states-presidential-election-p03] Harris did improve compared to Biden among voters making over $100,000 a year.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/2024-united-states-presidential-election-p03] NBC News found that Trump made larger gains in counties with tougher housing markets.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/2024-united-states-presidential-election-p03] Almost every incumbent party worldwide facing election in 2024 lost vote share, including in South Africa, India, France, the United Kingdom, and Japan.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/2024-united-states-presidential-election-p03] Among democracies, over 80 percent saw the incumbent party lose support compared to the last election.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/2024-united-states-presidential-election-p03] This is the first time this has ever happened since 1905 (when data was first recorded) and the first time in the history of democracy, as universal suffrage began in 1894.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/2024-united-states-presidential-election-p03] All 50 states and the District of Columbia shifted rightward compared to 2020.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/2024-united-states-presidential-election-p03] Trump's gains in nearly all geographic areas and among nearly every demographic group provides strong evidence of anti-incumbent backlash.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/2024-united-states-presidential-election-p03] The shifts toward Trump were much less in the swing states where both campaigns focused compared to safe states.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/2024-united-states-presidential-election-p03] The two states with the largest shifts toward Trump, New York and New Jersey, were both won by Harris.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/2024-united-states-presidential-election-p03] Harris had very little room to fall in the swing states, given that Biden had won most of them by very small margins in 2020.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/2024-united-states-presidential-election-p03] Statistician and election analyst Nate Silver argued before the election that the national electoral environment was difficult for Democrats.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/2024-united-states-presidential-election-p03] This view was also shared by *The New York Times* political analyst Nate Cohn.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/2024-united-states-presidential-election-p03] After the election, Silver felt that Harris was a replacement-level candidate who did much better than Biden would have, but was unable to separate herself from Biden's record and was negatively perceived by swing voters due to her previous positions.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/2024-united-states-presidential-election-p03] Amy Walter, editor of the nonpartisan *The Cook Political Report*, also argued that the electoral environment was inherently difficult for Harris because the top issue for voters was inflation during the Biden-Harris administration.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/2024-united-states-presidential-election-p03] Ronald Brownstein of *The Atlantic*, who spoke with members of Harris's campaign, argued that the extent of Biden's unpopularity and public discontent with the economy proved too much for Harris to overcome.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/2024-united-states-presidential-election-p03] Brownstein compared the election to the 1968 presidential election (when unpopular incumbent Lyndon B.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/2024-united-states-presidential-election-p03] Johnson withdrew from the race and Vice President Hubert Humphrey lost to Richard Nixon) and the 1980 presidential election (when unpopular incumbent Jimmy Carter lost to Ronald Reagan due to stagflation and the 1970s energy crisis).
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/2024-united-states-presidential-election-p03] Members of Harris' campaign stated after the election that their internal polling never showed Harris ahead of Trump and they did not believe that Harris was the favorite to win the election.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/2024-united-states-presidential-election-p03] David Plouffe, a senior campaign advisor to Harris, claimed that even making the race competitive was a win for Harris' staff.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/2024-united-states-presidential-election-p03] The opportunity to elect Harris as the first female U.S. president proved to be less important to voters than issues like the economy and immigration.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/2024-united-states-presidential-election-p03] Results of VoteCast, as reported by Fox News, find that 13% of voters chose "the fact that Kamala Harris would be the first female president" as the single most important factor to their vote.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/2024-united-states-presidential-election-p03] Even so, polls have shown that voters support backing a female candidate while also acknowledging the challenges they might face on the campaign trail.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/2024-united-states-presidential-election-p03] 18% in one of the polls said that it is extremely or very important to them personally that the United States elects a woman president in their lifetime.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/2024-united-states-presidential-election-p03] A September 2024 AP-NORC poll found that 34% of respondents thought that the fact that Kamala Harris is a woman would help her get elected.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/2024-united-states-presidential-election-p03] A slightly larger 38% thought that it would hurt her, while 26% didn't think it would make a difference.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/2024-united-states-presidential-election-p03] An AP-NORC poll from December of the same year found that about one-quarter said that it was extremely or very likely that the country would elect a woman president in their lifetime.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/2024-united-states-presidential-election-p03] A January 2024 Gallup poll found that 93% of Americans would vote for a generally well-qualified person for president who happened to be a woman.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/2024-united-states-presidential-election-p03] The survey found swing state Biden 2020 non-Harris voters ranked Gaza as less important than non-swing state voters.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/2024-united-states-presidential-election-p03] An analysis released by Democratic-leaning data firm Catalist in May 2025 found that Trump's victory rested on support from voters who were less engaged with politics, as well as weakened support and turnout for Harris from a range of Democratic-leaning groups.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/2024-united-states-presidential-election-p03] Nearly half of the 2024 electorate cast ballots in the previous four federal elections, representing an increase of nine points from 2020 and seven points from 2016, and Harris won under 50 percent of these voters, outperforming Biden's and Hillary Clinton's respective performances.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/2024-united-states-presidential-election-p03] In contrast, Harris won 48 percent of voters who only voted in two or fewer of the previous four federal elections, underperforming Biden and Clinton, both of whom won at least 54 percent of those voters.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/2024-united-states-presidential-election-p03] Jennifer Agiesta of CNN reported that new and infrequent voters in 2024 were more likely to be from Democratic-leaning groups but also less likely to have college degrees, a trait increasingly tied to Republican support.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/2024-united-states-presidential-election-p03] 15% of those who voted for Biden in 2020 did not vote in the 2024 election.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/2024-united-states-presidential-election-p03] 78% of White voters supported Trump in 2024, a lower level of support for him among this group than in 2020 and 2016.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/2024-united-states-presidential-election-p03] Fewer Black voters supported Harris in 2024 than they did the Democratic candidates in the 2020 and 2016 elections.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/2024-united-states-presidential-election-p03] Tonks tied the result to the party's prioritization of professional class workers and suburbs over working class, blue-collar voters.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/2024-united-states-presidential-election-p03] He argued the shift away from working-class voters had been occurring since the late 1960s in response to the Vietnam War and the growth of the tech industry.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/2024-united-states-presidential-election-p03] Of the electoral jurisdictions that Harris won – 19 states, DC, and Nebraska's second congressional district – all except New Mexico had above-average educational attainment.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/2024-united-states-presidential-election-p03] CNN's Edward-Isaac Dovere felt that some of Harris' problems, such as difficulties with her staff, could have been solved, but other problems such as her ties with Biden could not.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/2024-united-states-presidential-election-p03] Dovere mused that had Biden stepped down earlier, the Democratic Party might have had the time to launch a proper primary campaign.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/2024-united-states-presidential-election-p03] He also mused that Walz was chosen because he could not "outshine" her, and that this reflected her "newfound confidence and her long-standing insecurity".
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/2024-united-states-presidential-election-p03] *The Economic Times* cited surveys showing "broad negative sentiment" about the economy, and Harris being "relentlessly hammered" by Trump during campaigns about this.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/2024-united-states-presidential-election-p03] Harris campaigning at multiple events with former Republican representative Liz Cheney has been suggested as a contributing factor as to why she lost.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/2024-united-states-presidential-election-p03] Charlie Cook, founder of the nonpartisan *The Cook Political Report*, said that swing voters broke in favor of Trump due to anger over inflation associated with the Biden-Harris administration, causing Trump to sweep the swing states.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/2024-united-states-presidential-election-p03] However, Democrats did better in down-ballot races, meaning Trump did not have a strong coattail effect.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/2024-united-states-presidential-election-p03] *The Atlantic*'s Ronald Brownstein argued that the Democratic Party's success in the 2022 midterm elections, when Trump was not on the ballot, had led them to underestimate Trump's support.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/2024-united-states-presidential-election-p03] Democrats also performed better than Harris in down-ballot races, suggesting voters likely assigned their blame over the economy on the Biden-Harris administration rather than the Democratic Party at-large.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/2024-united-states-presidential-election-p03] *Vox*'s Nicole Narea highlighted inflation outpacing wages in certain industries, rising unemployment, and rising consumer debt and falling savings as key economic indicators that Democrats "may have missed".
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/2024-united-states-presidential-election-p03] According to exit polls, voters whose top issues were the economy and immigration largely voted for Trump.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/2024-united-states-presidential-election-p03] NBC noted a Democratic strategist's contention that male voters' belief that they were "being left behind, that society doesn't have a place for them" was a major factor in men's support for Trump.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/2024-united-states-presidential-election-p03] The network contended that Trump's approval ratings among non-college-educated and middle-income voters, especially among Latinos and young men, showed that he had made strides in his promise to assemble a multiracial, working-class coalition.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/2024-united-states-presidential-election-p03] Trump increased his support from Hispanics from 2020 to 2024, especially near the Mexican–American border and in areas impacted by recent immigration.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/2024-united-states-presidential-election-p03] Several observers pointed to shifting habits in how Americans consume media and a growing lack of trust in mainstream news outlets.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/2024-united-states-presidential-election-p03] Trump embraced alternative media through podcasts and online streamers such as Joe Rogan, Adin Ross, Theo Von, and the Nelk Boys.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/2024-united-states-presidential-election-p03] *The New York Times* reported that such avenues "presented a way for Mr.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/2024-united-states-presidential-election-p03] Trump to sidestep more confrontational interviews with professional journalists, where he might face tough questions, fact-checks and detailed policy debates.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/2024-united-states-presidential-election-p03] The influencers he met with rarely challenged Mr.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/2024-united-states-presidential-election-p03] Post-election research showed that nearly 40% of young voters got their news from social media influencers, and that a majority of those influencers leaned right.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/2024-united-states-presidential-election-p03] Journalist Elizabeth Spiers argued that Trump's strong support among young white men could be attributed to his campaign "channeling what psychologists call 'hegemonic masculinity'".
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/trump] The venture has faced widespread condemnation from ethics experts for Donald Trump's conflicts of interest related to the project and his presidential duties.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/trump] During the second Trump administration, Trump has promoted $Trump and taken actions that have raised the value of the meme coin, contributing to a substantial increase in his net worth.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/trump] The Trump meme coin was launched on January 17, 2025, three days before Trump was inaugurated as president of the United States.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/trump] The lack of a public announcement initially led to concerns that the cryptocurrency was a scam and might have no association to the president-elect.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/trump] Several hours later, Trump announced $Trump on his X and Truth social accounts.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/trump] The meme coin website described it as the "only official Trump meme".
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/trump] Its logo is a digitally-stylized image of Trump raising his fist after surviving the attempted assassination in July 2024.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/trump] A disclaimer said that the coin was "not intended to be, or the subject of" an investment opportunity or a security and was "not political and has nothing to do with" any political campaign, political office or government agency.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/trump] The terms of the offering prohibit coin buyers from joining any class-action lawsuits against the project and assert indemnity against any claims.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/trump] Trump promoted the coin on the night of its ICO while a "Crypto Ball" was underway.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/trump] After its launch, its price soared by over 300% overnight.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/trump] Within two days, it became the 19th most valuable form of cryptocurrency in the world, with a total trading value of nearly $13 billion, and a total of $29 billion worth of trades based on a $64 value of each of the 200 million tokens issued by the afternoon of January 19.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/trump] *The New York Times* reported that Trump affiliates controlled an additional 800 million tokens that, hypothetically, could be worth over $56 billion, potentially making Trump one of the richest people in the world at an estimated net worth of $63.8 billion.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/trump] A March 2025, a *Financial Times* analysis found that the crypto project netted at least $350 million ($314 million from the sale of the tokens and $36 million from fees).
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/trump] However, by July 2025, *New York* reported that the president's holdings in the coin were only worth about $93 million.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/trump] This was contradicted by reporting in *The New Yorker* in August 2025 suggesting that holdings held by Trump through a partnership "are potentially worth several billion dollars" and that actualized profits from the meme coin were $385 million.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/trump] In April 2025, the top 220 holders of the coin were offered dinner with the president, and the very top 25 holders would receive a special VIP White House tour.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/trump] Following the announcement, the coin jumped more than 50%.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/trump] Analysis found that leaked information about the promotion allowed certain traders to make bets on the coin before it was publicly announced.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/trump] According to *The New York Times*, certain buyers in interviews and statements said they "bought the coins or entered the dinner contest with the intention of securing an action by Mr.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/trump] The purchase was the first known instance of a China-linked firm buying Trump's cryptocurrency.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/trump] TikTok is facing a ban in the US, although Trump has postponed the decision several times.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/trump] According to *The New York Times*, at least twenty investors sold or transferred their holdings in $Trump on May 12.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/trump] The bidding process allowed certain investors to profit; in one instance, an investor, known only as "Noah", purchased US$2.2 million in $Trump before the contest and sold it at the end of the contest, profiting over US$950,000.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/trump] In an apparent effort to stop the sell-off, the social media account associated with $Trump promised to give investors who kept their coins a non-fungible token known as "Trump Diamond Hand" and that they would earn reward points.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/trump] Several investors were able to attend the dinner for only the cost of trading fees by shorting $Trump.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/trump] According to NBC News, the winners of the contest collectively spent US$394 million.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/trump] References to a tour of the White House were later removed from the dinner's website; a senior Trump official stated that the administration was not conducting a tour for the investors.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/trump] The "black-tie optional" dinner was held at Trump National Golf Club Washington, D.C. in Sterling, Virginia.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/trump] Before the dinner, protesters had gathered to condemn the gathering, shouting, "Shame!" The menu featured filet mignon, pan-seared halibut, and a "Trump organic field green salad".
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/trump] An attendee who spoke to *The Verge* described "pretty light" security, Trump's limited presence and his speech—delivered behind a podium with the presidential seal—and a private afterparty at the Washington Marriott Capitol Hill hosted by Memecore.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/trump] Trump's speech was approximately fifteen to twenty minutes long.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/trump] Four of the highest-paying investors, including Justin Sun, were given US$100,000 Tourbillon watches.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/trump] The dinner was Sun's first visit to the United States since being investigated by the United States attorney for the Southern District of New York in 2021.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/trump] MemeCore, a cryptocurrency company, invested US$19.3 million to become the second-largest holder; Cherry Hsu, the company's chief business officer, stated that he was interested in sharing its "vision and mission" with Trump and other attendees.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/trump] The largest holder was an account belonging to HTX that was believed to be associated with Justin Sun.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/trump] Javier Selgas, the chief executive of Fr8Tech, told the Securities and Exchange Commission that he intended to purchase US$20 million in $Trump in an effort to convince Trump to lower tariffs on Mexico.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/trump] Through a guest list and social media, the *Times* later identified many of the attendees, including Sun and the former basketball player Lamar Odom.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/trump] The dinner posed ethics concerns and opportunities for foreign influence.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/trump] Wyoming senator Cynthia Lummis and Senate majority leader Thom Tillis expressed concerns over the dinner.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/trump] Citizens for Responsibility and Ethics in Washington's Donald Sherman described it as "one of the most blatant and appalling instances of selling access to the presidency".
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/trump] Merkley and Senate minority leader Chuck Schumer introduced a bill to ban senior executive branch officials—including Trump—and their family from profiting off of cryptocurrency.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/trump] Merkley additionally asked the Office of Government Ethics to investigate the dinner.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/trump] The Senate Homeland Security Permanent Subcommittee on Investigations's investigation into cryptocurrency businesses involving Trump broadened to include the dinner.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/trump] Maryland representative Jamie Raskin, the ranking member of the House Committee on the Judiciary, later initiated an inquiry into the dinner.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/trump] The late-night television hosts Jimmy Fallon and Jimmy Kimmel ridiculed the dinner for its attendees and its apparent corruption, respectively.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/trump] In April 2026, the top buyers of the $Trump coin attended a Mar-a-lago event where they got potential facetime with Trump.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/trump] The Citizens for Responsibility and Ethics in Washington (CREW) condemned the event and the $Trump coin as unethical.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/trump] According to the meme coin's website, ownership of the token is primarily concentrated in two Trump owned entities: CIC Digital LLC and Fight Fight Fight LLC, which together hold 80 percent of the coins remaining after the ICO.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/trump] Trump's personal profit under this ownership structure is unclear.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/trump] The holdings are scheduled for gradual release over three years.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/trump] Some crypto executives and investors said Trump had undermined the credibility of the industry they had worked hard to build by selling coins known for their speculative nature and extreme volatility.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/trump] They also noted Trump's brazen conflict of interest by setting crypto market policies while directly benefiting from participating in the market.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/trump] Some noted its similarity to a "rug pull", in which a coin is launched and quickly abandoned, leaving early investors with steep losses.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/trump] *The Wall Street Journal* reported "Even the most ardent Trump supporters reached a breaking point when the $MELANIA token launched less than 48 hours after" $Trump, with one urging Trump to fire the advisor who recommended it.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/trump] Erik Voorhees, a prominent Bitcoin investor, criticized the coin as "stupid and embarrassing".
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/trump] Others discussed its lack of any utility beyond enriching Trump.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/trump] Ethics experts criticized the crypto venture and government watchdogs.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/trump] The venture and the possibility of foreign governments buying the coin and enriching Trump was highlighted as possibly violating the Constitution's foreign emoluments clause.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/trump] Critics said it could allow special interests and foreign governments to seek to buy influence with the president.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/trump] The release of $Trump was condemned by ethics lawyers, including Adav Noti, the director of the Campaign Legal Center, and Jordan Libowitz, the vice president for communications at Citizens for Responsibility and Ethics in Washington.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/trump] Nick Tomaino, a former executive at Coinbase, described Trump's ownership and the timing of the cryptocurrency as "predatory".
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/trump] Anthony Scaramucci, a former White House Communications Director during the first Trump administration and current crypto investor, described the coin as "Idi Amin level corruption" and said that the launch of the coin was bad for the cryptocurrency industry.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/trump] He added, "Now anyone in world can essentially deposit money into bank account of President of USA with a couple clicks." Brendan Fischer, the deputy executive director at *Documented,* an investigative news outlet, said, "The timing of this launch cannot be a coincidence.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/trump] Some analysts described it as a pump and dump scheme, and a "disaster".
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/trump] A forensic analysis commissioned by *The New York Times* concluded that 813,294 wallets lost $2 billion by trading the coin while the president's company and partners profited about $100 million from trading fees.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/trump] According to *Fortune*, "Less than three weeks after its release, President Donald Trump's meme coin has produced more losers than winners.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/trump] Unlike the Hatch Act, it would introduce a private right of action for anyone harmed by purchasing such assets.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/trump] After the launch of the $Trump meme coin, Trump's wife Melania launched her own meme coin, $Melania on January 19, 2025.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/trump] The launch of the $Melania token was partially handled by Hayden Davis, who later played a key role in orchestrating the $Libra cryptocurrency scandal.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/trump] Davis admitted to his involvement in "sniping" the $Melania and $Libra tokens, a legally-questionable practice similar to front running.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/trump] From President Trump's 2024 inauguration day to the end of November 2025, the price of the $Melania token fell 99%, while the price of the $Trump token fell 86%.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/trump] Representative Jamie Raskin released a report finding that following an investigation by Democrats on the U.S.
[src:2024-united-states-presidential-election/trump] The report, titled *Trump, Crypto, and a New Age of Corruption*, also found that Trump dismantled anti-corruption and financial integrity safeguards and pardoned people who were regarded as "corporate cronies" in order build his cryptocurrency empire.
